DEBUG: Raw artifact: ['6783eaf5-34a0-4359-b876-5d94930d9d74', 'Mafia Dismissals and Economic Growth', 8, [[['8feb9033-b616-490c-b81e-7debc300e1bd']]], 3, None, None, None, None, None, [1776163504, 621964000], None, None, None, None, [1776162739, 876334000], [['Generate a 20-slide presentation based on Fenizia and Saggio (2024). STYLE: Strictly white background, no other background colors. STRUCTURE: 1. Title/Introduction, 2-3. Motivation (costs of OC), 4. Literature Review, 5. Institutional Background (CCDs), 6. Data (INPS, Treasury, ANAC), 7-10. Detailed Methodology on Matched DiD (matching algorithm, probit, econometric specification, parallel trends assumption), 11-14. Main Results (Employment, Firms, Dynamism, Real Estate Prices), 15-18. Mechanisms (Political turnover, connection breakage, Mafia sectors), 19. Robustness Tests (Shocks, Spillovers), 20. Conclusion. Use references to Figures 1-10 and Tables 1-4 from the sources. Academic and rigorous tone.', 'en', 2, 3], 'Mafia Dismissals and Economic Growth', [[['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQEyirgpaPLY38pUOsYIJfqopqSpMYD8XlDSIyBmLLL637Nh4fdlpI0bW3dlYfqmFitACkqfVJ6dnaH_B1NTEbF_jIh8p_rTPWtTMa5Xvjw9fNVEMN7o-pcb8tOcTi3L8epSjk5gGjyZQ4cdKJ1VibOEYb39UgK7Zp5LZMU=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Title slide for a presentation on the economic impact of dismissing mafia-infiltrated city councils in Italy.', 'ORGANIZED CRIME AND ECONOMIC GROWTH: EVIDENCE FROM MUNICIPALITIES INFILTRATED BY THE MAFIA\n\nAlessandra Fenizia and Raffaele Saggio (2024)\n\nA matched difference-in-differences analysis of the long-run economic impact of dismissing mafia-infiltrated city councils. Applying this design to the universe of Italian social security records reveals that neutralizing the political tentacles of organized crime is a catalyst for economic development.'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQGDPHHm8zoLIuUS3r0GavrkJQhnNmm8AEt9JBDusBF_oIYvnLu-AGHgRsxGkrVPxUhX0AekJe5JCQDzUZxl1Dwg6ln9F8B4-hrG-mlr-aVwsxpkzSpjU5dLVE6CvVIbXtZCPk88GUjyMhiA2Sx26_6KFYDqaaLSEjq78YQ=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Slide outlining the known crisis of organized crime and the empirical gap in research regarding state intervention.', 'MOTIVATION & LITERATURE REVIEW\n\nTHE KNOWN CRISIS\n- Organized crime preys on healthy businesses, weakens competition, and hinders growth (Pinotti, 2015).\n- Millions live in areas controlled by criminal networks, facing violence and displacement (Blattman et al., 2021).\n- Deeply entrenched origins stretching back centuries (Acemoglu et al., 2019).\n\nTHE EMPIRICAL GAP\n- How does the State regain control and reassert legitimacy in heavily infiltrated areas?\n- Do aggressive attempts to remove organized crime ultimately manifest in long-run economic development?'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQHh7m-zrxEf_OG-Yl16r6PsSTH63NT9dChhPrJfqYhmIVTkdWAytcUzg9EES0j5Coh7ePGQmx1q_EHrH6sVKdODeQcqx5pRiBusTbSXB8dVaTOfO20m-PuCcnuJiG4BgK_w1uM3O1CXpl_exjjqOW01RcCiUB3ue9olO_A=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'A timeline detailing the steps of a City Council Dismissal (CCD) from investigation to new elections in Italy.', "THE ANATOMY OF A CITY COUNCIL DISMISSAL (CCD)\n\n[Timeline showing five sequential stages connected by a blue line]\n\n- Unrelated Police Investigation: Evidence of Mafia ties emerges during routine policing (not triggered by economic failure).\n- Commissione d'Accesso: A 3-month formal investigation by the Ministry of the Interior.\n- The Dismissal: Mayor, executive committee, and city council are entirely dismissed.\n- External Commissioners: Career civil servants assume full legislative/executive powers for 24-36 months.\n- New Elections: The municipality returns to democratic control (k=3 in the empirical model).\n\n[An inset map of Italy highlights several municipalities in the southern regions of Sicily, Calabria, and Campania in red and orange, indicating the frequency of CCD events.]"], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQHvYv1zmc35cCU6D7vTdcON38TLkIOmpd5BoGLlDR0PsiGS_vbO7GZP-ggJ1Y04uOB9DK79zkGsZbyiZuyOFAozuSaJOjj7M382gT5nSjqp8Q4I_1Hah6-aeXOshWrcgNmsbYjSITUhfwmAgbLau0iwHQfAooD6X9_teQ=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Overview of the administrative data sources and a balance matrix comparing treated and control municipalities.', 'AN UNPRECEDENTED ADMINISTRATIVE DATA INFRASTRUCTURE\n\n- INPS (1983-2017): Universe of matched employer-employee social security records. Captures highly localized small business dynamics.\n- Italian Treasury (2002-2015): Complete administrative data on real estate prices (residential, office, and industrial).\n- ANAC / Ministry of the Interior: Complete data on local politicians, corporate board ownership, and public procurement contracts.\n\nTHE PRE-CCD BALANCE MATRIX\n- Metric: Population; Treated (T): 15,522; Control (C): 15,004; p-value: 0.84\n- Metric: Number of Firms; Treated (T): 220; Control (C): 280; p-value: 0.15\n- Metric: Average Daily Wage; Treated (T): 73.21 euros; Control (C): 72.28 euros; p-value: 0.51\n\nControl municipalities provide an exceptionally balanced counterfactual prior to the CCD event.'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQEPfHnGCNKPjYvg1ToY96aVmNi8MOmVz3jlw0b3OCpXv1mdg3Ik7gacManDOk2shZr7Jm3-2GTlCEbvQXeg52BGbtIXH85uQaXUaEqK4ho6uz_N2xr9JkNewnTRp9pBbTmRJC07ZkMX7BNk7piLw1wONJNBdlAgTgWbIQ=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'A funnel diagram showing the four-step process used to select 211 matched pairs for the research design.', 'CONSTRUCTING THE MATCHED DIFFERENCE-IN-DIFFERENCES DESIGN\n\n[A funnel-shaped flow diagram illustrates the sample selection process]\n\n- Universe of Municipalities [Large rectangle]\n- Step 1: Grouping by Region & Year. Grouping 245 treated municipalities by region (r) and the year they were subject to the CCD (t*). [Arrow points to smaller trapezoid]\n- Step 2: Out-of-Region Restriction. Crucial to prevent spatial spillover effects by restricting donor pool to never-treated municipalities in other regions. [Arrow points to smaller trapezoid]\n- Step 3: Probit Propensity Matching. Estimating a probit model on lagged employment, wages, and population. [Arrow points to a final small blue rectangle]\n- Result: 211 Matched Pairs (87% of all events, highly balanced).'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQGO-ynwSLKAZqTQJZtIicH0Kdxi5o0mO3dpmu8H7CSIpNBCVgPzpKJ1ja4SmB1F8xJ9tq-Yei0uzspI56Pxi2HTXFmLvKmk4PV37aW_zwtyp3ljxdH9bafHhDI8yAnJtlteLAlHuyQljafIaFNopTK8fTZrq8wK-ihshkY=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'The econometric equation and parallel trends assumption used to estimate the treatment effect of CCDs.', 'ECONOMETRIC SPECIFICATION & THE PARALLEL TRENDS ASSUMPTION\n\n[A mathematical formula for y_mt is shown, including variables for municipality fixed effects, region-by-time fixed effects, and a treatment indicator.]\n\n- Municipality fixed effects: alpha_m.\n- Region-by-time fixed effects (absorbs regional shocks): lambda_r(m),t.\n- Treatment indicator: Weighted by the log number of baseline firms to prevent tiny municipalities from driving estimates.\n\n[A line graph with a horizontal axis showing years from -3 to 3 and a vertical axis for Treatment Effect.]\n\nPlacebo tests show no evidence of differential pre-trends in the years leading up to the event, validating the strict non-economic triggers of the CCD procedure.'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQEGbdPnPRJ93-jullumgCFZ4lhsmFZrtnU2drQu3oVYCk1JzClf6oeijylcKUK6t3XC26kx8A273rfe0ol9BF9jRQhqEVC6DXERvMtO23yKKN1zYXk8dGaFkfxeiEfz35hO-Q5vgiTUigfMB95K--CdD3o98IrcUfzlY_g=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Two line graphs showing significant long-run increases in employment and number of firms following CCDs.', 'CCDS TRIGGER SUBSTANTIAL LONG-RUN ECONOMIC GROWTH\n\nIMPACT ON EMPLOYMENT\n[Line graph with error bars shows employment levels remaining flat until year 3, then rising sharply to a 16.9% increase by year 9 post-intervention.]\n\nIMPACT ON NUMBER OF FIRMS\n[Line graph with error bars shows the total stock of firms remaining flat until year 3, then increasing to a 9.4% gain by year 9.]\n\nThe economic engine only ignites once democratic control is restored under new leadership (indicated by a vertical dashed line at year 3 labeled New Democratic Elections).'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQEMWU_tXpFSU5pNGBlpb-LJZH0TG1hrZ4bE0DB462RTmjVQVR79Pa3XwK8SMqJt5DdvD6z0ZMgCQRKW4JHrbXaSa5jY52AhPyVWCsLnzA7-BuyJUrNhdr64jnuuY4kVrHyLyMO9jpFdDX3KRN2AdmhKKfPfjfkDJNyzScY=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Charts showing increased firm dynamism and a surge in youth and previously unemployed workers entering the workforce.', 'UNLOCKING ECONOMIC DYNAMISM AND YOUTH EMPLOYMENT\n\nFIRM DYNAMISM\n- Surge in Firm Entries: +25% [Large blue bar]\n- Slight Increase in Exits: +4% [Small grey bar]\nInsight: CCDs do not prop up dead firms; they inject market dynamism.\n\nTHE DEMOGRAPHIC INFLUX\n- Share of New Entrants: [Line graph shows the percentage of all entrants and young entrants rising steadily after year 2, reaching approximately 4% and 2% respectively by year 9.]\n- Share of Previously Not Employed Workers: [Line graph shows a similar upward trend starting after year 3 for both all and young previously unemployed workers.]\n\nThe average wage dips (-4.6%) entirely because of a massive influx of young, previously unemployed workers entering formal entry-level jobs. This acts as a direct structural barrier to Mafia recruitment among vulnerable youth.'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQFyl09_BJFDMdLP-PUfnwMkNwcXA_rMhw_nJG5bqq87lVY5Cdxyt6FkgyIJp-jiF2Owtqq6tzWzc5kLpCWup8bfdeXo6rqu1qqkbnQ2alAbNHl0uNeLmu40yI7pjT8a_VyZjECGQ-yvEWj1RPGZoojURw9PcDs4v3ZqDYA=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Comparison of industrial versus residential real estate prices to validate real economic growth post-CCD.', 'VALIDATING REAL ECONOMIC EXPANSION VIA REAL ESTATE DEMAND\n\nAdministrative employment data is subject to formalization effects. Real estate transactions are not. If growth is real, land demand must rise.\n\nINDUSTRIAL REAL ESTATE PRICES\n[Line graph shows a sharp upward trend in business property prices starting after the restoration of democratic control at k=3, resulting in a 15% long-run increase.]\n\nRESIDENTIAL REAL ESTATE PRICES\n[Line graph shows fluctuating data with error bars crossing zero, indicating no significant effect on residential prices or population movement.]\n\nThe localized surge in business property prices proves the employment effects represent real, net-new economic activity, not mere formalization of the informal sector.'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQFMamj8xi9mXNwmq8dbJb0bzW-RbfwmW5zdvCqNxTMz8fUgeLpkDc_ETIAuF6W9wKir1K3BeHvW_MYHRHdAWQfW8kpXPi2x5UTHcS58zAB0iXZcrcX8t0jPOX2SbLGwsnTBZMCvX8j5cUbio88ZdrOWpE4Jc4lEIqCAGC0=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Graphs illustrating a shift towards first-time, female, younger, and more educated politicians after a CCD.', 'MECHANISM I: A RADICAL SHIFT IN VOTER PREFERENCES\n\nCCDs do not change who runs for office; they change who wins.\n\n- +13% First-time Politicians: [Line graph shows the share of first-time politicians jumping from roughly 0.1 to over 0.3 after the intervention.]\n- +6% Female Politicians: [Line graph shows an increase from below 0.2 to roughly 0.4. This is noted as a 55% relative increase against patriarchal culture.]\n- Higher Educational Attainment: Newly elected officials possess significantly higher degrees of formal education. [Icon of an upward arrow]\n- Younger Demographics: [Line graph shows the average age of politicians dropping by 2 full years after the intervention.]'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQEBhvp1kd1lGwg-6VNe-4C973ZwA2xcSSXCLVMhtHfg_5k-lq-JbMRtt5cURlwvOe-VKOp2wdLeQa4DOOSaETwUdFlA-VlAm1CSRthMDK1jNgBxsZmPBg48Rrr_Alqe3AFVX0Uwcz4mCQ40duIcQ3wlqtPSh2KTjRVh53Q=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Data showing a significant reduction in the links between politicians and corporate boards following a CCD.', 'MECHANISM II: SEVERING ILLICIT CORPORATE CONNECTIONS\n\nThe Mafia relies on political connections to enforce market monopolies. Post-CCD, the physical administration of these links is broken.\n\nBROAD POLITICAL CONNECTIONS\n[Line graph shows the share of connected politicians dropping from approximately 0.8 to around 0.2 following the intervention at time zero.]\nA 5 percentage point drop (33% relative reduction) in political/corporate board overlap.\n\nTARGETED MAFIA SEVERING\n[Line graph shows the share of corrupt politicians serving on corporate boards falling from nearly 0.8 to almost zero immediately following the intervention.]\nAn 80% reduction in the likelihood that dismissed corrupt politicians retain positions of corporate power post-CCD.'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQFfD4AGb46XOd86-gLTKZc905luL7LH4t6O3bRveIDeEYwhufspuDUtUQajTJlj-jeEkprluy0Ynlq92STjtDY3l14IN-w7kUr36tXrZ-Sj7eliqs1lwaP2Hl4Owxpq-cB36HSRUrv6aLKfy4y0MIgGxIvI8v90YYCQ5iA=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Charts showing growth in previously monopolized sectors and employment losses for Mafia-connected firms.', 'MECHANISM III: UNLOCKING MONOPOLIZED INDUSTRIES\n\nWHERE DOES GROWTH OCCUR?\n- Log Number of Firms (Mafia vs. Non-mafia sectors): [Line graph shows over 20% firm growth exclusively in high-risk sectors like construction and waste disposal, while non-mafia sectors remain flat.]\n- Log Number of Employees (Mafia vs. Non-mafia sectors): [Line graph shows a similar sharp upward trend for employment in mafia-risk sectors.]\n\nWHO LOSES?\n- Log Average Employment (Connected Firms): [Line graph shows that firms previously connected to dismissed politicians experience a massive and immediate drop in employment levels.]\n\nEconomic growth is driven entirely by non-connected firms entering newly liberated, previously monopolized markets. Prior procurement winners suffer significant post-CCD losses.'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQE_HLJKGbACs_ctTA9cfJunktvPt7En0vSXFKq_9RLghuOpK1tH4m2vdHNPTgrErEhWRFqY-ruNa_Ijcg_RrsD3X7PVsR9Fd5bQt79tbpPtVJnouKuuiTO_t8KkZC_LBF0RRbugUcLQqAsxPLS1xOgq74GtE6nnlq-9oYw=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'A comparison table showing that only Mafia-related CCDs with high political turnover result in significant growth.', 'MECHANISM SYNTHESIS: RE-CENTRALIZATION VS. MAFIA ERADICATION\n\n[Table comparing outcomes for Mafia-Related CCDs and Alternative (Non-Mafia) CCDs]\n\nTHE TRIGGER OUTCOME\n- Mafia-Related: Massive economic growth.\n- Alternative: Negligible/flat economic effects. Simply installing experienced bureaucrats only accounts for approximately 20% of growth. [Line graph shows a flat trend for non-mafia CCDs.]\n\nTHE POLITICAL OUTCOME\n- Mafia-Related: High Political Change: Explosive economic growth (+16.9%). [Line graph shows much higher growth for municipalities with an above-median share of non-incumbent politicians.]\n- Alternative: Low Political Turnover (Old Guard re-elected) results in zero economic growth.\n\nVerdict: Growth only occurs when the Mafia is fundamentally weakened and voters systematically reject the old regime. Legitimacy is the true catalyst.'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQEry7jiNvZQsxqzqmOzM_FLoCOzjB-8Nddq9gOdKI0pmzwnMuQXWdkMBKyN4wBTptl4Nw4eVooojt0Sl2CJmkHS5OlGKH57px1wLhCNOsqzM07e4l6ZAlk54zYbLcR2QYguuQJsuEWsIAsM04ewYU0Z6WM-Dnp-OVKUMuU=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'A checklist confirming that various alternative explanations for economic growth have been ruled out.', 'ROBUSTNESS & ALTERNATIVE EXPLANATIONS DEFEATED\n\n[A list with large checkmarks next to each point]\n\n- Increased Police Spending? No. Expenditure on justice and police shows no systematic difference leading up to the CCD.\n- Government Stimulus? No. Central government transfers and infrastructure spending do not scale up post-CCD.\n- Spatial Spillovers? No. Spillovers to neighboring towns are actually positive, and results hold when dropping all control pool units within a 20km radius.\n- Coincidental Regional Shocks? No. Results are robust to excluding the massive shock years of 1993 (Cosa Nostra attacks) and 2012 (Monti structural changes).\n- Control Pool Contamination? No. Driven by strict out-of-region matching and verified by in-region matching robustness checks.'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQF9cc9skzCExoYZ88WtQ0_Axuc9kw7gtrvTXKEbHzSqWvIyNN6Yfd7PVPPCksW30X4Xn8DaRGAHH8rsGftyJUHrqU17NThLYHu3LF1l2DnrqDOgQoCVsCSqOv44WT1821B0lKjduWPsrxLV7zpdzqPBFZphGMv4eGWNwQ=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Summary of key findings on how targeting corrupt institutions builds legitimacy and long-term economic growth.', 'THE LONG-TERM PAYOUT OF TARGETING CORRUPT INSTITUTIONS\n\n1. LEGITIMACY SPURS GROWTH\nNeutralizing the political tentacles of organized crime is a highly effective, place-based economic development policy. Depressed regions leap forward when monopolies are broken.\n\n2. INSTITUTIONAL TRUST REQUIRES TIME\nThe economic engine does not ignite instantly. It takes 3+ years—and a return to democratic elections—for a climate of risk to transform into a climate of trust.\n\n3. INSTITUTIONS > ILLEGAL ACTS\nTargeting corrupt institutions directly yields massive economic returns without the violent backlash traditionally associated with targeting specific illegal activities.\n\nCity Council Dismissals transition municipalities from a climate of fear to a climate of trust, proving that state legitimacy is the ultimate foundation of economic dynamism.']], 'https://contribution.usercontent.google.com/download?c=Cgpub3RlYm9va2xtEkYSD2FydGlmYWN0c19tZWRpYRozCiQ2Yjg4NzYxYi0yMzM4LTQwM2MtYjJhOC02Y2NjMTU5YTViYzASCxIHELeYmtjZERgB&filename=Mafia_Dismissals_and_Economic_Growth.pdf&opi=96797242', 'https://contribution.usercontent.google.com/download?c=Cgpub3RlYm9va2xtEkYSD2FydGlmYWN0c19tZWRpYRozCiQzYzgzYjEzYS03MTYxLTRlODktOWZmZC1mZWZhMzk5OGE5ZTkSCxIHELeYmtjZERgB&filename=Mafia_Dismissals_and_Economic_Growth.pptx&opi=96797242'], None, None, 5, None, 'MTc3NjE2MzUwNC02MjE5NjQwMDA=']
DEBUG: Asset 6783eaf5-34a0-4359-b876-5d94930d9d74 type=8 status=3
DEBUG: Raw artifact: ['2d52a407-b896-4af8-bb38-c8f39cea4c6a', 'Economic Growth after Mafia Dismissal', 8, [[['8feb9033-b616-490c-b81e-7debc300e1bd']]], 3, None, None, None, None, None, [1776159249, 308235000], None, None, None, None, [1776158237, 568408000], [['Create a detailed 20-slide presentation based on the paper "Organized Crime and Economic Growth" (Fenizia and Saggio, 2024). The structure must be typical for an economics presentation: \n\n1. Slide 1: Title and authors.\n2. Slides 2-3: Motivation (economic costs of organized crime, state intervention).\n3. Slide 4: Literature Review (combating criminal governance, economic impact of OC).\n4. Slide 5: Data Sources (INPS, Treasury, Ministry of Interior, ANAC).\n5. Slides 6-10: Detailed Methodology on Matched Difference-in-Differences (matching algorithm, propensity score covariates, econometric specification/equation, parallel trends assumption, and tests for validity like Figure G2).\n6. Slides 11-14: Main Results including Employment and Firms (Figure 2), Economic Dynamism (Table 3), Wages and Worker Flows (Figure 3), and Real Estate Prices (Figure 4).\n7. Slides 15-18: Mechanisms explaining results (Re-centralization vs. Mafia Weakening, Political Turnover (Figure 6), Political Connections (Figure 7), and Mafia Sectors (Figure 8)).\n8. Slide 19: Robustness Tests (spillovers, alternative matching, different samples).\n9. Slide 20: Conclusions and Policy Implications.\n\nStrictly use the original data, tables, and figures from the paper without invention. Ensure the methodology slides are technically rigorous. All content must be in English.', 'en-US', 2, 1], 'Economic Growth after Mafia Dismissal', [[['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQFjoE6T_wpXqbCz-2mT0lyhOzVZDuONoB4w4fAx9SSzMpLYK0j0g5Rsawo-kl3SxNy3xi-rn6q5b4XToNBa3wpoa3At8B_IzhQspNZx4_ocQBBgn0iC7tgBDzk4vb6F_lXpieJtdF6LsS2UH2NnBKIJMtMP3dukcs49_fo=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Title slide for a presentation on organized crime and economic growth in Italian municipalities.', 'ORGANIZED CRIME AND ECONOMIC GROWTH\n\nEvidence from Municipalities Infiltrated by the Mafia.\n\n\nAuthors: Alessandra Fenizia (George Washington University) & Raffaele Saggio (University of British Columbia and NBER).\n\n\nPublication: American Economic Review, 2024.\n\n\n[Map of Italy with various municipalities highlighted by orange glowing nodes and interconnected web lines.]'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQE_Y7QnfW4cz6hm0C2JaPw-5Ku2KkpZMnB4Caa6uKHsgChX8koun56NOKOQuPuGCa-X0SjqD9YPPsJHzXV7gChnIyEFdX8NI90IUQI8SueGIFjivUlTDhCf93b7ywlc7h4pwEF6wJNukIXmuC4E-hWnvQsQZ1d4w5dBgoI=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Slide outlining the social and economic costs of criminal governance and identifies an analytical gap in evidence.', 'THE ENTRENCHED COSTS OF CRIMINAL GOVERNANCE\n\n- Social Displacement: Hundreds of millions of people live in areas controlled by criminal organizations globally. Thousands are displaced by accompanying violence.\n\n\n- Economic Predation: The Mafia thrives on illegal activities, preys on healthy businesses, and creates an environment of extortion that stifles competition.\n\n\n- Growth Stagnation: Decades of infiltration weaken local institutions, halt innovation, and systematically hinder long-run economic growth in affected regions.\n\n\nThe Analytical Gap: While the spread of the Mafia is well-documented, we lack empirical evidence on whether aggressive state attempts to remove organized crime ultimately manifest in long-run economic development.'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQGqAHoumX1_q-yECxesKy3aVXan3VghS7ouno_YdSoPfBKHVf0cqbz7GGBeLvYgy2In6gWuUJbg6s98RAQNKdfeGPZAbF5AemXBL6RwOsBzTQC98IJJcSDW6nW0fzSJwIfJ_XrbiHXzwXtkeBRXMEfgBb4CrC3FZKyFNHQ=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Explanation of the City Council Dismissal policy and its historical scale in Italy through a map and graph.', 'THE STATE’S ULTIMATUM: CITY COUNCIL DISMISSALS (CCD)\n\nTHE POLICY BLUEPRINT\n\n\n1. Investigation: Ministry of the Interior uncovers connections between local politicians and organized crime.\n\n\n2. Dismissal: The central government completely dismisses the mayor, executive committee, and city council.\n\n\n3. Replacement: External commissioners (experienced civil servants) take over with full legislative/executive powers for 24-36 months.\n\n\nScale: 245 unique municipalities subject to CCDs between 1991 and 2016.\n\n\n[Panel A: Line graph titled "City council dismissals due to mafia infiltration, 1991–2016" showing a sharp peak in the early 90s, followed by lower fluctuations with a smaller peak around 2012.]\n\n\n[Panel B: Map of Italy with regions shaded in red to represent the number of CCDs, with the highest concentration in Southern Italy.]'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQELDU-vRC2rAtSEil2eEH4cjUwCyJBeQbB8ZGZKzJgog-xk86GrrBvShbEgsk_yF8UMWGHgvNd3q-9sNv02Co0pEZQydwFwAajGJYPFZYVFuNaO3bJv3_zjKOPn7BeGjN-GBN4nLNGsrYB8V7jawrvcbF179-Md2mSHf8s=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'A 2x2 matrix positioning the research of Fenizia and Saggio as a focus on institutions and long-run economic growth.', 'LOCATING THE EVIDENCE GAP IN INSTITUTIONAL RECOVERY\n\n[A 2x2 matrix with the vertical axis representing Short-term Disruption versus Long-run Economic Growth, and the horizontal axis representing Focus on Illegal Markets versus Focus on Institutions.]\n\n\n- Economic Impact of OC: The Mafia stifles competition, hinders firm performance, and reduces aggregate economic activity (Pinotti 2015; Colonnelli & Prem 2022). [Box located in Top-Left quadrant]\n\n\n- Combating Criminal Governance: Crackdowns on drug trafficking or money laundering often lead to unintended consequences—homicides rise, network violence expands (Dell 2015; Slutzky et al. 2019). [Box located in Bottom-Left quadrant]\n\n\n- Fenizia & Saggio (2024): Studying an aggressive, direct intervention against corrupt local institutions to measure the subsequent return of formal economic growth and trust. [Highlighted box located in Top-Right quadrant]'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQH4iMCneJuWA6cCxhzzcw4TKzxdB1MZxPvsw79PJcugQODePiVKp58tXinL9Xts0H9-0WdTZY3aQbQmG39GwKZ9V-imZ07f66IxXw3cy8of1cQICg-TVJ9UyHkNzNEk0cNLPQIiVPU_cArqCi9ZYe3QJretZVU4aFoyx98=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], "Overview of the diverse administrative data sources used to study the municipality's economic and political landscape.", 'AN EXHAUSTIVE ECOSYSTEM OF ADMINISTRATIVE MICRO-DATA\n\n[Diagram shows "The Municipality" at the center with four arrows pointing outward to different data sources.]\n\n\n- Social Security Data (INPS): Matched employer-employee dataset (1983-2017). Tracks universe of non-agricultural firms, wages, days worked, and worker flows. Crucially captures small businesses.\n\n\n- Ministry of Interior & Cerved: Local politicians (1986-2020) and firm ownership (2003-2017). Allows cross-referencing political mandates with corporate board seats.\n\n\n- Real Estate (Treasury): Complete administrative data on residential, office, and industrial real estate prices (2002-2015). Highly resistant to informal sector underreporting.\n\n\n- Public Procurement (ANAC): All public works contracts, allowing the identification of connected firms operating before and after the CCD.'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQGglR9VGsSVCyiZeMMYzgkC2TqgFRNbgxGYYKLVRI_7RAxS98hmJQUZMv3ZsppDmnP4wTvLrkUmyHWhPDGTEfuq349RC6-n0aGycE7Q8SIrfuu8fm4YdVruKuZo5C54PB3uvxqI3NRviJSZGYyYjmYKTHplmwtD_ICxK2o=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Description of the three-step matching algorithm used to create a statistically valid control group for the study.', 'CONSTRUCTING THE COUNTERFACTUAL: THE MATCHING ALGORITHM\n\n[Three arrows point from Step 1 to Step 2 to Step 3.]\n\n\n- Step 1: Out-of-Region Donor Pool. To prevent contamination from economic spillovers, potential control municipalities are restricted to regions that did not experience the specific CCD event.\n\n\n- Step 2: Propensity Score Probit. A probit model relates the CCD event to historical economic and demographic covariates (lagged log earnings, employment, population, local industry shares).\n\n\n- Step 3: Matched Pairs. Each treated municipality is paired with the untreated out-of-region municipality possessing the closest propensity score.\n\n\nResult: 87% of events successfully matched (211 out of 245 CCDs).'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQFek_5Va3Z4xUyZ9VT7CmeH1pSwmjqBYseFx6j0j60OKzpkzNJ1RcViaIb6blYNTli2PEt7yfD2NFlA9EiGy8GQ5m4sHpLs59b8W43m74s-dHOGofaYUeOKRs81BMyjzQy7XEZCaIE8JFoFoWJznylsNmpq8bqX_H8hIw=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Table showing that the treatment and control municipalities are statistically balanced across key metrics before intervention.', 'A BALANCED FORENSIC BASELINE PRIOR TO INTERVENTION\n\nDespite systemic depression in Southern Italy, the matching algorithm successfully balances treatment and control across critical economic dimensions in the year before the CCD.\n\n\n- Population (1991): Treatment (T) 15,522, Control (C) 15,004, p-value=0.84\n\n\n- Number of Firms: Treatment (T) 220, Control (C) 280, p-value=0.15\n\n\n- Avg. Daily Wage: Treatment (T) €73.21, Control (C) €72.28, p-value=0.51\n\n\n- Share of New Entrants: Treatment (T) 0.15, Control (C) 0.13, p-value=0.21\n\n\n- Electoral Turnout: Treatment (T) 0.77, Control (C) 0.79, p-value=0.08\n\n\nTakeaway: Control municipalities represent a statistically valid counterfactual for observing the dynamic effects of the CCD.'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQEZySb3xw9o3-dcOfgJ0ihws-oKl88NJcs6e7dmyrI8ZUTrSDSTKyu3kG9hMdAv_3BqkKAfyBgwFH1OfGechEtZVUaT8m68xak-jrtVvplu59i8YLBzNfrF5zEPG3zO9MEzATB4XpYQdDDA9-z1MvoxQdLBJjb3GH3rcA=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Econometric model used to estimate the dynamic treatment effects of City Council Dismissals on economic outcomes.', 'ISOLATING THE DYNAMIC TREATMENT EFFECTS\n\n[Econometric equation: y_mt = alpha_m + lambda_r(m),t + sum over b from k=a of theta_tilde_k 1{t = t*_m + k} + sum over b from k=a of theta_k 1{t = t*_m + k} times CCD_m + u_mt]\n\n\n- Outcome variable (e.g., log employment) for municipality m in year t.\n\n\n- Fixed Effects: Absorbing municipality-specific characteristics and region-by-time shocks.\n\n\n- The crucial event-time parameters: Identifies the difference in outcomes between treated and counterfactual municipalities relative to the year prior to the CCD.\n\n\n- Treatment dummy.\n\n\nWeighting: Regressions are weighted by the log number of firms in the year before the CCD to prevent tiny municipalities from driving estimates.'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQHaIZzOy2tNEJVLI3XXDDVgwSrdYdkrd02CKkEHJQZhmJEUy6tec6MFvAC29tqRcq5ksjkW8L9YJ15T7twzaRdy7WttdeLNFp6YClN5QdOsLLPzoyTN36CEbnm5YM_zkHGJlb5rerXk-Z_GFWdPFYnUK0IrM6kYdWBL0vM=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Slide explaining the defenses for the parallel trends assumption, addressing potential economic divergence triggers.', 'VALIDATING THE PARALLEL TRENDS ASSUMPTION\n\nThe Core Threat: Did economic divergence trigger the CCD, rather than the CCD causing the economic divergence?\n\n\n- Institutional Defense: The law dictates a strict, multi-step evidentiary procedure. CCDs are triggered by police wiretaps, uncovered political connections, or violent crime—never by poor municipal financial performance or procurement delays.\n\n\n- Empirical Defense: Placebo tests evaluating the event-study coefficients for the years prior to the intervention (k < 0) show virtually zero evidence of differential pre-trends across a variety of economic outcomes. The treated and control units tracked together perfectly before intervention.'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQHucs0BmXLorEmv4PXMzWIF2-ZivXm9G4GsNwhFy1ekwR4vgJRF1ZxUIG-yqTSxtEyG2Y35KlLPpbbCYZnNwI7WjjRMvEfZOFyOdI-TxlRGj7C76SzdL_ZCnZMYGKOFJxH--3M8uMmpyBzZN_sJ6sxvV7FNwWZwe_LfqLE=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Analysis showing that economic changes are not driven by increased spending on local police or justice systems.', 'RULING OUT LAW ENFORCEMENT CONFOUNDERS\n\nThe Hypothesis: Increased media coverage induces municipalities to increase local police spending, triggering the CCD and independently driving economic changes.\n\n\n- Justice System Expenditures: [A graph shows a flat line around zero throughout the timeline from before to after intervention.]\n\n\n- Local Police Expenditures: [A graph shows a flat line around zero throughout the timeline from before to after intervention.]\n\n\nConclusion: The subsequent economic boom is not a mechanical result of heavy-handed local policing. Expenditure data invalidates this confounder.'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQGkub4JPh1YKSPFyqflD7xt1Gh94euG0uHXuLeN5PNJNGJepZqK3eESUEcJePSqKG7bBOPIvsHK3fD5l7g9fiIThgpWePgSyEbNjdrtAGo9ceDyciE_pr-ifB9tNTRNlyNN1VPZk6g71ncV0VO6pAhMjwDOfw9wh2UoANI=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Event-study graphs showing a significant increase in employment and number of firms starting three years after a CCD.', 'THE EVIDENCE: A SURGE IN REAL ECONOMIC ACTIVITY\n\nThe Catalyst Timeline: Employment tracks the control group perfectly before the CCD. Explosive growth begins at Year 3—exactly when new city councils are elected.\n\n\n- Log Employment (+16.9% Increase): [Event-study graph shows a flat trend before Year 0 and a steady upward trend starting after Year 3.]\n\n\n- Log Number of Firms (+9.4% Increase): [Event-study graph shows a flat trend before Year 0 and a steady upward trend starting after Year 3.]\n\n\nConclusion: The subsequent economic boom is not a mechanical result of heavy-handed local policing. Expenditure data invalidates this confounder.'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQFo9vkLOjE-Iphl3jF92y7_ZGNkYc5EmliBhNv4fogIAQm0vq03F7OfE8VnfCkybIbDJNdC-vYyDPO_l4ZjTPBo3e--RybiQHFVU0NIw_76Kh4zr2K3Tt_A-AT2fGw08PDuE3bFhOSV2TLmLicxRYpHsynmvN0jP1jwvSk=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Diagram showing that the net increase in firms is driven by a surge in entries that outweighs exits.', "ECONOMIC DYNAMISM: ENTRY OVERPOWERS EXIT\n\nThe Mechanics of Growth: The 9.4% net increase in firms is not driven by propping up failing businesses. It is driven by a massive surge in firm entry. The CCD breaks local monopolies.\n\n\n- Firm Entries (+6.1 percentage points): The share of new firms that didn't exist before the CCD increases by nearly 50% relative to the pre-period mean. [Large arrow points right into a central box labeled Total Firms.]\n\n\n- Total Firms (Long-run Net +9.4%): [Central box representing the net result.]\n\n\n- Firm Exits (+4.3 percentage points): Inefficient or corrupt firms lose their protection and exit the market. [Small arrow points right out of the central box.]"], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQGh9Q-NHXU0E8e-IVWhlKHPfSlunmA7v6wFxGZEWBv3c_kT0DkGv9ZQb9I1qUJHwnasIzuagAHV5cbco5wG8LbGYMv6JoCjXcETIezDpXXf8U1TtdpO1LxfQusnVy2Dgt0CWa8VpK6w2a-L92ZabybkCv07Q_iO_kpdszc=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Explanation of why average wages decline following a CCD, citing an influx of young, previously unemployed workers.', 'THE WAGE PARADOX: DRAWING YOUTH INTO THE FORMAL ECONOMY\n\nThe Anomaly: While total employment skyrockets, average daily wages decline by 4.6% in the long run. Why? [Line graph shows average wages declining after Year 0.]\n\n\nThe Resolution: Breaking the Mafia Pipeline. The wage drop is driven entirely by a massive influx of new, previously un-employed workers taking entry-level jobs, diluting the average. Incumbent worker wages do not fall.\n\n\nShare of previously not-employed workers: [Line graph shows a significant increase in the share of previously not-employed workers, especially for young workers, starting after Year 3.]\n\n\nCritical Context: Youth unemployment in Southern Italy is historically high. Young men are the prime recruitment target for criminal organizations. The CCD successfully diverts them into formal employment.'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQFuvK_SJcSs5_ybJoOdGWKCwN6ToPymdu_6xSme-h0wBUI1yXcjBkwxHxqTbLntMpdH2_LIDsJ-U9Pu9QMvrsCf-LPkUUkmWwWuKD09LNMlPDbZR0ZyILE4AWrjrx2B84f0JKG2kzV6XdbAywoBvTljLKeTXePY3u0bOX4=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Comparison of industrial and office real estate prices, showing growth specifically in industrial sectors after a CCD.', "CAPITALIZATION: THE INDUSTRIAL REAL ESTATE BOOM\n\nThe Skeptic's Question: Is this real growth, or just informal workers being formalized on paper?\n\n\nThe Verification: Real estate transactions are incredibly difficult to underreport. Genuine expansion demands physical land and factories.\n\n\n- Industrial Prices: Surge by +15%. Perfectly mirrors the employment growth curve, taking off at Year 3. [Graph shows industrial real estate prices increasing significantly after Year 3.]\n\n\n- Office Real Estate: No Lasting Effect. Growth is distinctly driven by industrial and manufacturing activity. [Graph shows office real estate prices remaining flat around zero.]"], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQHpX4Wk_sSL57e5GtGBbA8iCP-KE9-ZrsHGNo3A9xzlxIm0Kaux0h761YFKqKHA4csd7KQmwQZ1aJiQMCEalyOgNDk-45bvvwuZX0GlNoVOlZNfxetYSYQGh79W-UjNcRpSMw1_CDJ1VIE3dvxgwHknNtq3k9SKkrYKajQ=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], "Slide testing two hypotheses to conclude that CCD success comes from weakening the Mafia's monopoly, not state efficiency.", "ISOLATING THE MECHANISM: EFFICIENCY VS. LIBERATION\n\n- Hypothesis A: Re-Centralization (State Efficiency). CCDs work simply because external bureaucrats are better at managing towns and central transfers increase. STATUS: REJECTED. [Graph shows flat employment trends for Mafia-unrelated CCDs.]\n\n\n- Hypothesis B: Mafia Weakening (Breaking the Monopoly). CCDs work strictly because they sever the Mafia's illicit control over the local economy. STATUS: VALIDATED.\n\n\nCCDs work strictly because they sever the Mafia's illicit over the local economy. The data systematically proves this through political turnover, severed connections, and sectoral growth in high-risk markets."], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQGvWYnIq3pxecquggs-cnT6_GjF_DRb_FOn_ba_Nvi36MmmYhy_NufLSm1yOSE2c5mFh4Ql73O1gNOHTQX7NH72Jf0l5PwiQzRzBvJ_q2N9NQ1ZDxfktXMCZYpKQXPfJvDAdRa8Hsq5DSpOrsE2t8yQ2DND2FHuJd3oTks=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Visualization of shifting voter behavior toward younger, female, and first-time politicians after a CCD intervention.', "THE POLITICAL PIVOT: VOTERS REJECT THE OLD GUARD\n\nThe Mechanism: By dismissing the council, the state signals the Mafia cannot protect its politicians. Voter behavior fundamentally shifts.\n\n\n- First-Time Politicians: +13 percentage points (a 24% increase). [Graph shows an increase in first-time politicians after Year 0.]\n\n\n- Gender: +6 pp more likely to be female (striking a direct blow to the Mafia's patriarchal power structures). [Graph shows a decrease in the share of male politicians after Year 0.]\n\n\n- Age: On average, two years younger. [Graph shows the average age of politicians decreasing after Year 0.]\n\n\nSummary Note: The candidate pool running for office doesn't change; voter behavior does. The state intervention breaks the spell of electoral fear."], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQFX7MGcN7iw6DFud2WOLK-SSbAG_ZrPW7hylVY_ZB115Mvic44xTKeiyqaiF8wxVkMOQzafliteofqmxtFCWSCKGTfDGL2zquDvGB-BgaAiwP1ASKTKhCtpQEpn39Yb25da5kxwtqbiH9D8YGMJFiT3f90KYWn8WfL8kg=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Data showing that dismissed politicians lose power in local firms and that previously connected firms experience employment drops.', 'SEVERING THE ARTERIES OF CORRUPTION\n\nThe Mafia relies on political connections to enforce monopolies and win contracts.\n\n\n- Breaking Connivance: The specific Mayors and Vice Mayors dismissed by the CCD are 80% less likely to hold positions of power within local firms afterward. [Graph shows a sharp drop in employment for firms where dismissed politicians were formerly connected.]\n\n\n- The Fall of Connected Firms: Firms that won public procurement contracts before the CCD (allegedly via corruption) experience sharp drops in employment. The economic boom is entirely driven by unconnected firms. [Graph shows a decline in employment for connected firms after Year 0.]'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQE2d6l4r_fEPeF6hxCGPt-Hh4IO_TKBar5IKWVzariveJgwQYNBJsdD2RN8dp9VE3S6XDjXsPHoI8bfCbtSrzSH_t9YkFUlZMdcLPPh_IH3fODVVyustqNAqvRsWUrW7NKasqiV3jf2sJpCzt1_mdXbMegmd3yUZ__rLEE=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Graphs highlighting growth in high-risk sectors and confirming that political turnover is necessary for economic recovery.', 'SECTORAL LIBERATION & THE NECESSITY OF POLITICAL CHANGE\n\nThe Mafia lives on portal look in fitd-Mafia Sectors for leading denome in alnpitalism. [Text on slide appears partially garbled.]\n\n\n- Targeted Growth in High-Risk Sectors: Firm entry explodes specifically in "High-Risk Mafia Sectors" (construction, waste disposal, concrete). The Mafia\'s enforcement of monopolies in these sectors was broken. [Graph shows an increase in number of firms for high-risk mafia sectors versus flat non-mafia sectors.]\n\n\n- The Ultimate Proof: Political Turnover is Required. What happens if a CCD fails to replace the old politicians? In municipalities that re-elect the old guard, there is zero economic growth. The miracle only materializes in towns that experience above-median political turnover. [Graph shows employment growth only for municipalities with high political turnover.]'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQHWIrVjVSkaLblOK-B0pq7NrNL0MLoehkqGrMUbJWBBDlKjKVJuGQDKL8ejTPYOxjH4kOypxy6jBl27UO0B3ve6MG-29w9nKG2xleZJ4gVdTIiivE0AzyT74_pExMr0p_KY0QGfIbo1JpJbPs0eDoMd1l5nUJfOJRfoLlE=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Summary of robustness tests confirming the stability and validity of the research findings under various conditions.', 'ROBUSTNESS & STRESS TESTING THE FINDINGS\n\n- Geographic Spillovers Accounted For: Dropped all control municipalities within a 20km radius of any treated unit to prevent contamination. Findings hold. (Growth does not come at the expense of neighboring towns).\n\n\n- Resilience to Macro-Shocks: Excluded the massive CCD spikes of 1993 (Cosa Nostra terror attacks) and 2012 (Monti government). Findings hold.\n\n\n- Alternative Matching Algorithms: Relaxed the out-of-region restriction and matched within the same region. Included socio-political variables in the algorithm. Findings hold.\n\n\n- Sample Stability Confirmed: Restricted the model to a balanced panel and isolated municipalities that experienced only a single, unique CCD event. Findings perfectly hold.'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQE9nql_OR1p2B7CwAd8sx-y3JlOJwIZUH5pLhMESfKBpTbemTKaKiBc_0qSC9-pQXg4Ae9LtXOzxR3jd_IsON_YQM87yYH3KyTrpU6cOKZoHbCMIQaG2IAtkOgozwJtfTWJLK-8aKGNTjZci3kmqR0VCwOiB6wN_FNbJWE=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Final summary emphasizing that targeting corrupt institutions leads to a transition of trust and long-run economic growth.', "THE VERDICT: INSTITUTIONAL LEGITIMACY AS ECONOMIC STIMULUS\n\n1. The Power of Direct Institutional Targeting: Targeting illegal activities (drugs, money laundering) often breeds violence. Directly targeting the corrupt institutions themselves successfully breaks the Mafia's grip without sparking violent retaliation.\n\n\n2. A Transition of Trust: By demonstrating the state will not tolerate infiltration, citizens fundamentally change their voting behavior, and new entrepreneurs confidently enter historically monopolized, high-risk sectors.\n\n\n3. The Long-Run Return on Intervention: The economic upside of state intervention is massive but delayed. The +16.9% employment boom materializes only after new, clean councils are elected. Eradicating criminal monopolies is a prerequisite for long-term economic development."]], 'https://contribution.usercontent.google.com/download?c=Cgpub3RlYm9va2xtEkYSD2FydGlmYWN0c19tZWRpYRozCiRmYWFiYzUyYS05YmY0LTRlYmYtYWNjMi00ZWVlZWQ1Yzc3NWQSCxIHELeYmtjZERgB&filename=Economic_Growth_after_Mafia_Dismissal.pdf&opi=96797242', 'https://contribution.usercontent.google.com/download?c=Cgpub3RlYm9va2xtEkYSD2FydGlmYWN0c19tZWRpYRozCiRjZjFkNjA3YS0yM2Y2LTQxNmEtYWQ5ZC1jYzY1YTk4YzMyMDUSCxIHELeYmtjZERgB&filename=Economic_Growth_after_Mafia_Dismissal.pptx&opi=96797242'], None, None, 5, None, 'MTc3NjE1OTI0OS0zMDgyMzUwMDA=']
