DEBUG: upsert_asset values: ('2d52a407-b896-4af8-bb38-c8f39cea4c6a', 'ce65bb2f-2c69-4493-a2c0-c68fe17aa54f', 'slide_deck', 'completed', '[\'Create a detailed 20-slide presentation based on the paper "Organized Crime and Economic Growth" (Fenizia and Saggio, 2024). The structure must be typical for an economics presentation: \\n\\n1. Slide 1: Title and authors.\\n2. Slides 2-3: Motivation (economic costs of organized crime, state intervention).\\n3. Slide 4: Literature Review (combating criminal governance, economic impact of OC).\\n4. Slide 5: Data Sources (INPS, Treasury, Ministry of Interior, ANAC).\\n5. Slides 6-10: Detailed Methodology on Matched Difference-in-Differences (matching algorithm, propensity score covariates, econometric specification/equation, parallel trends assumption, and tests for validity like Figure G2).\\n6. Slides 11-14: Main Results including Employment and Firms (Figure 2), Economic Dynamism (Table 3), Wages and Worker Flows (Figure 3), and Real Estate Prices (Figure 4).\\n7. Slides 15-18: Mechanisms explaining results (Re-centralization vs. Mafia Weakening, Political Turnover (Figure 6), Political Connections (Figure 7), and Mafia Sectors (Figure 8)).\\n8. Slide 19: Robustness Tests (spillovers, alternative matching, different samples).\\n9. Slide 20: Conclusions and Policy Implications.\\n\\nStrictly use the original data, tables, and figures from the paper without invention. Ensure the methodology slides are technically rigorous. All content must be in English.\', \'en-US\', 2, 1]', None, {})
  [+] Notebook: Fueling Organized Crime: The Mexican War on Drugs and Oil Theft
      ID: 3d95540f-cda5-4e49-8069-3a2b4f3d19c9
DEBUG: Raw artifact: ['1c41e288-db04-4612-97fb-1f4c2af2a1a0', 'Drug Wars Fueling Oil Theft', 8, [[['c2400f02-d8c4-40cc-8dea-ea871698e140']]], 3, None, None, None, None, None, [1774867019, 626140000], None, None, None, None, [1774866401, 501531000], [['Create a 15-slide academic presentation in English with a white background. Use only original figures and tables from the source material. Focus exclusively on the Regression Discontinuity Design (RDD) framework. The structure must include: 1. Title/Intro, 2. Research Question/Motivation, 3. Leapfrogging model (Figure 2 panel c), 4. War on Drugs context (Figure 3), 5. Oil theft context (Figure 1), 6. RDD Strategy (Equation 4), 7. Political Alignment (Figure 4), 8. Validity: Balancing tests (Table A.9), 9. Validity: Density test (Figure A.7), 10. Validity: Placebo 2006 (Table A.10), 11. Main Results: Visual (Figure 6), 12. Main Results: Estimates (Table 3), 13. Robustness: Permutation tests (Figure A.10), 14. Robustness: Bandwidth sensitivity (Figure A.8), 15. Dynamic Effects & Policy (Figure 7).', 'en-US', None, 3], 'Drug Wars Fueling Oil Theft', [[['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQGLu5cNzQQAJeE97-fnYO6yE8-ehzbXONA3ULgOJsc9WGDJjwtiC9TF7kSKXMPd8ZdTlTTTNWPl5kZGTZnglGrltQ2ZJonjyADl_YD4DACXfyA8Bjg-S1lpK_owupq9sgz5-9fLH7qx_U8QzZ6ZUkrLIQmXdWmJIVeqpPo=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Title slide for "Fueling Organized Crime" regarding the link between the Mexican drug war and oil theft.', 'FUELING ORGANIZED CRIME: THE MEXICAN WAR ON DRUGS AND OIL THEFT\n\nHow the 2006 military crackdown unintentionally pushed drug cartels into the large-scale oil theft business.\n\nGiacomo Battiston, Gianmarco Daniele, Marco Le Moglie, Paolo Pinotti\n\n\nKey Insight\nUsing a Regression Discontinuity Design (RDD), we prove that local electoral outcomes determining the intensity of the drug war directly caused a massive reallocation of cartel resources into pipeline tapping.'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQHJeHe-96HF2A89AWIkJnG1Fr7j_ctytmjIKt9Cjx2CtMpflu5NM84g_mNgmOnohSDxUiQ-TtwPZwMo1J0Z7Y7EP-aU6zVfYpObc7V4NJGtPzGUTrvrTpv6VYV_Chp4n-AHN9Wi7HDAtR34-qqVHCw1aTdQ8JHsyOAwOfw=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Flowchart and steps showing how drug crackdowns led to cartels pivoting into oil theft using an empirical strategy.', 'DOES LOCALIZED DRUG REPRESSION UNINTENTIONALLY SPUR NEW CRIMINAL SECTORS?\n\nTHE PROBLEM\n- Crackdowns target traditional markets (Narcotics).\n- [Arrow points down]\n- Cartels adapt rather than exit the criminal marketplace.\n- [Arrow points down]\n- Unintended Consequence: Massive pivot to new, highly lucrative sectors.\n\n\nTHE EMPIRICAL STRATEGY\n- 1. Isolate municipalities with physical oil pipelines.\n- 2. Leverage close mayoral elections (PAN party margin of victory) from 2007-2009 as a natural experiment.\n- 3. Prove that a narrow PAN victory (a proxy for a federally coordinated local crackdown) caused a definitive spike in illegal oil taps.'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQHfwEFHOgwqRyGkeuwgTVZonTp0m7Q3akp0V-NMrqWZ4-ALVhV4rvYxfIpOy1fpUT2gCsOSnLlw59qteZq8BuQ3mWIefqk1hbXIEw1tC1q9wkUVv2WmYynKC7yFBqRQHloeEyUgD7IK5IlAdOfN5m8Ea0RZs_C7vJ6nlI8=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Two maps showing how the 2006 crackdown fractured a stable cartel oligopoly into a complex landscape.', "THE 2006 WAR ON DRUGS FRACTURED A STABLE CARTEL OLIGOPOLY\n\n1990s: Stable Oligopoly\n[Map of Mexico divided into four large, solid-colored regions: blue, red, yellow, and purple.]\nFour stable incumbent cartels. Minimal inter-cartel conflict. Stable collusion networks.\n\n\n[Green arrow labeled 2006 Military Crackdown points to the second map.]\n\n\n2011: Fractured Landscape\n[Map of Mexico showing hundreds of small, multicolored regions, indicating fragmentation.]\nDeployment of 45,000 federal troops fractures the landscape. Emergence of desperate 'Challenger' cartels (Zetas, Familia Michoacana) seeking new revenue streams to survive."], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQGC1WqIefvOBrJADH7f6t7M9NX_r-oXwMsiSMmEv8yLmf0OC-dC502NVbBByoUUIeDnQCyCa8V9i_KoCYJp9IPE1_OeJkfGmBHy2-MA8O5MLWuqP8IA5n437btnvY_I1AtVBOOe1Uf5ti77DiSzBaQiX6Ky8mjNA98-TI8=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Line graph showing a massive increase in illegal oil taps and homicides following the 2007 War on Drugs launch.', 'THE RISE OF THE HUACHICOLEROS IMMEDIATELY FOLLOWED THE DRUG CRACKDOWN\n\n[Line graph comparing Homicide rate per 100,000 inhabitants on the left Y-axis and total illegal oil taps on the right Y-axis from 2000 to 2018. A vertical red dashed line marks 2007.]\n\nPresident Calderon launches the War on Drugs.\n\n\n- Hockey-stick growth: from hundreds of taps pre-2007 to over 15,000 by 2018, generating $1-2B annually. [Green arrow points to the sharp upward trend of the red line representing oil taps.]\n- Pemex Green: [A green line representing homicide rates spikes after 2007, dips around 2014, and rises again.]\n\n\nIndustrial-scale tapping requires engineering expertise and capital—hallmarks of organized cartels, not petty thieves.'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQHw0liiBBdhMccrThq3ZNiMf7kPdkUbM1uo3RPfv2UClB49rKr_UT5WyULMNdpVnuI9FzkXGYcohx2n301PP-S35a_zqR_hEfuIJFX6u4CsCk4iKfi8rOqKLl22NJf1KldzGvh8FMNXUUbZJh_MzMRUDR7z6cvrUjiigYI=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Economic quadrant chart explaining how challenger cartels "leapfrog" incumbents into the oil theft sector.', 'CHALLENGER CARTELS LEAPFROG INCUMBENTS TO DOMINATE THE NEW OIL SECTOR\n\n[A quadrant graph with Relative Entry Cost on the X-axis and Relative Productivity of Oil vs Drugs on the Y-axis. A large green arrow points from the bottom-left to the top-right.]\n\n1. The Catalyst: Drug crackdown drastically reduces traditional narcotics profits. [Arrow points to "Drugs Only (Incumbents)" at the origin.]\n\n\n2. The Challengers: Smaller, non-dominant cartels have less to lose in the traditional market. [Arrow points to the middle of the "Both Sectors" diagonal path.]\n\n\n3. The Leapfrog: Challengers pay the initial fixed investment to enter the new, high-yield oil theft sector, leaving incumbents behind. [Arrow points to "Oil Only (Challengers)" at the top-right.]'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQF2Vtr7Cc-9Q_SsLZbE5wQyq0hJeSlGmlThmsnuZXtpOe41qD6feAip9RoEaCy3LRBk2spfZ27owTpvqOYCoXi53DImg3m6AYHifSmwrhTnE1oaZH_I6-vDiA9NsIktvaKyRmtozwHMNWDU9a2AafzOVvWLIlZTeJFz3jE=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Statistical slide explaining the Regression Discontinuity Design equation used to isolate causality.', "ISOLATING CAUSALITY THROUGH A REGRESSION DISCONTINUITY DESIGN\n\n[Regression equation: Taps_i = alpha + beta*PAN_i + sum(delta_k*MV^k) + sum(gamma_k(PAN_i * MV^k)) + chi_s + i_e + epsilon_i]\n\n- The Outcome: Average illegal oil taps per year (2007-2014). [Arrow points to Taps_i.]\n- The Running Variable: PAN candidate's margin of victory/loss in local elections. [Arrows point to beta*PAN_i and sum(delta_k*MV^k).]\n- The Treatment: A dummy for PAN victory. Proxy for intense, federally-coordinated local drug crackdowns. [Arrow points to sum(gamma_k(PAN_i * MV^k)).]\n- The Causal Estimand: The jump in oil thefts directly caused by the crackdown. [Arrow points from the beta variable to the text box.]"], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQG1VEHZGqq3jUWWi3XbJyauMnYtBROL4GRwsyYOxn7DHoFUAbJ_fyW0MNDH-LIwjHUMv0WH_A1QdP3bSlGu96TKnc5velO0N-tkiU6UF4sllVP0G-nmRjJWhZr5ffMznERMyZJAPdOfGc7QqfkBdeu4f70UADhk8GGsljc=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Two maps of Mexico showing the correlation between oil pipeline locations and illegal tap clusters.', "THE NATURAL EXPERIMENT RELIES ON A STRICT GEOGRAPHIC CONSTRAINT\n\nThe Opportunity: Mexico's refined oil pipeline network crosses only 313 municipalities. [Map of Mexico with a purple network of lines representing pipelines.]\n\n\nThe Action: Taps cluster exclusively along this infrastructure. [Map of Mexico where the same purple lines are covered by dense clusters of red dots representing illegal taps.]\n\n\nOur RDD estimates the effect of PAN mayoral victories strictly within the subset of municipalities traversed by pipelines. Without a pipeline, cartels cannot pivot to oil theft regardless of crackdown intensity."], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQHmqEkg3UuzloVhpV7ETGJRkDXt6sUb6FQF_zQ-rkM811J_0SYpFnG6rkXX2QnGp3ekfyV-M_19YsuR5Ry5E-GPfo9SNEUrphP-xuu9loyI9tU_lm91l5Fc4rs7V4fCDecL91QoEcRFnOX0DT8x_NOGgds3pQqAVrgnmg=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Table showing that municipalities with narrow election wins/losses have identical geographic and social traits.', 'VALIDITY 1/3: NARROW PAN WINNERS AND LOSERS GOVERN IDENTICAL MUNICIPALITIES\n\nDifferences in observable characteristics at the RD cutoff\n\n[Table showing geographic characteristics for Symmetric and Asymmetric bandwidths.]\n- Surface (km2): RD Effect -99.872, Robust p-val 0.894 | RD Effect -226.643, Robust p-val 0.751\n- Distance to closest pipeline (km): RD Effect -1.541, Robust p-val 0.540 | RD Effect -1.890, Robust p-val 0.380\n- Homicides per 1,000 inh. (2006): RD Effect 0.057, Robust p-val 0.329 | RD Effect 0.043, Robust p-val 0.490\n- No scholar. per 1000 inh. (15+ years) (2005): RD Effect -27.973, Robust p-val 0.691 | RD Effect 20.575, Robust p-val 0.742\n\n\nIs the natural experiment clean? Yes.\nAll p-values are significantly high (>0.10). At the zero-margin-of-victory cutoff, municipalities where PAN barely won are statistically identical to those where PAN barely lost in terms of geography, population, and prior crime.'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQH87wm49-KsWILQ8Yb9EGxsRultfKIhyoN28e4NPxgI3LJSpi0n8Ntxi7-CL1wmsuyCf5stqBW_btnQjsw88hp3yA0aK949xudozYFwOobhsZcDdMOqy5A9PsURKJ20ugcj-k_fLRdiol4BMshtnwfdpIp7gJo05Jnx5g=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'McCrary density test graph proving election outcomes were not manipulated, ensuring a clean experiment.', "VALIDITY 2/3: ELECTION OUTCOMES WERE NOT SYSTEMATICALLY MANIPULATED\n\n[Graph of a McCrary Density Test showing a smooth curve of data points across a vertical dashed red line at the zero margin of victory/loss.]\n\nThe smooth, continuous curve across the zero-cutoff proves there is no 'bunching' of data.\n\nPAN candidates did not systematically commit electoral fraud to push themselves just over the finish line. The assignment of treatment (crackdown) is truly quasi-from."], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQG99vxK3ubQ282Oy0hTdAOZjmU2KNPHZbbUOxZNWfxlVAUdOwfBus9EhgFHKTfiBeHOmaCYaK1W_pmXU08cQmMgGJMRPbKQRBFx3hesu6OTCLRZLSCqrfu-8mEc3XukP4BTRraoehsbMBy5zCe9N_c0t8mVOt4txLuwjJo=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Table showing that before the drug war crackdown in 2006, PAN victories had no effect on oil theft.', "VALIDITY 3/3: THE EFFECT DISAPPEARS ENTIRELY IN THE PLACEBO YEAR (2006)\n\nPlacebo estimates for 2006\n\n[Table showing eight columns of placebo estimates.]\n(a): Symmetric bandwidth\nPAN's victory: -0.229, -0.175, -0.204, -0.260, -0.345, -0.368, -0.364, -0.306 [Row highlighted in red].\n\n\nIf we run the exact same RDD model on data from 2006—the year before Calderon launched the federal War on Drugs—the effect vanishes. A PAN victory meant nothing for oil theft before the federal crackdown began."], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQEsyxgzDRkU0P6jUXhYSwvCBnOZwGKQ8w_HnBUQgxls0upAjbX23cpnurLW95VHgtZDr3m0p7_COmu6YCdpWCag-cGpEmkSZQj3BYxj9WfznyuSibDyE1WpxJ69LB-v2WMe6z_WlYwT9AOZUXf0zgk_OCQjQZ9B9n-6LNE=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Scatter plot demonstrating a sharp discontinuity in illegal oil taps at the zero-margin victory cutoff.', 'THE DECISIVE VISUAL PROOF: A MASSIVE SPIKE IN OIL THEFT AT THE POLITICAL CUTOFF\n\n[Scatter plot and regression lines showing illegal taps on the Y-axis and PAN\'s margin of victory/loss on the X-axis. A vertical dashed red line marks zero. The regression lines show a significant vertical gap, labeled "The Discontinuity," at the zero point.]\n\nExactly where the pro-crackdown PAN party crosses the threshold from losing to winning, illegal oil taps immediately jump upward. This is the causal footprint of the War on Drugs.'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQEB23OYE9BPSs-WYz2FqSmPgC6jYA87QVgjnC91UgzKshKdGorGz_xdUflx-xppie63c21Zg01S5IzN7EIW7BD3fUVgjmim0aJUZv75joFAlltkrEFCsifSkmV2tczvSDvnOMlwItyRhPFIm_jXOi4abYuqvwKOar3Xl0E=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Table showing that a marginal PAN victory doubled the baseline rate of illegal oil taps in municipalities.', "A MARGINAL PAN VICTORY MORE THAN DOUBLED THE BASELINE RATE OF OIL THEFT\n\nThe Intensity of the War on Drugs and oil thefts: RD estimates\n\n[Table showing eight columns of RD estimates. Values in the first two columns of the PAN's victory row are 6.580** and 3.964*, highlighted in green.]\n\n\nThe baseline average in pipeline municipalities was 5.3 taps per year.\n\nOur primary estimate shows a marginal PAN victory caused an average of +6.6 additional taps per year. The intense local drug crackdown literally doubled the scale of local oil theft."], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQH_DdXa7QfzzIOvqg680_zk4xud6bN61Rn69hI93Ujmu4itt-rz-9AtbTOXvcxn-4aETFayoP-DgvY_lA41seiVKkspW6RRfpALeoep95Vt6lqNVrz8rqYO8R-z377G-hrJFUCy9AYyiTD1DrMa37Hy2sgsGYr9WYasHA=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Histograms of permutation tests proving the observed oil theft jump is a statistical outlier, not an accident.', 'PERMUTATION TESTS PROVE THIS DISCONTINUITY IS A TRUE OUTLIER\n\n[Two histograms, one for Symmetric bandwidth and one for Asymmetric bandwidth, showing the distribution of results from 10,000 fake election cutoffs. Both show the true estimate, marked with a black vertical line at 9.065 and 10.09 respectively, far to the right of the normal distribution.]\n\nThe true estimate sits far outside the normal distribution, easily clearing the 95th percentile. This is not a statistical accident.'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQElqggBKX84wMfZaaegbFJzx_xiJOZHkVuAznlJG5IUSPqJ_TL-AuEbQw9nyUz-Hr-dNdBg9OyFi5LZjoCT11gJMxgENv_5g-8ljqPtiKCn-b4MfcKsVM9l8C9H7zOVB9b4xoBXMVSMGkkVyxKpPJiBC-MyykdmnwuxLHI=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Six graphs showing the jump in oil theft is consistent across various margin bandwidths and fitting methods.', 'THE CAUSAL JUMP REMAINS STABLE ACROSS ALL STATISTICAL BANDWIDTHS\n\n[Six scatter plots organized into three rows (20% Margin, 10% Margin, 5% Margin) and two columns (Linear fit, Smoothed fit). Each plot shows a consistent jump in illegal taps at the zero-margin line.]\n\nWhether we look at wide, medium, or ultra-narrow margins of victory, the structural break at the zero-cutoff remains clear and significant. The result is completely insensitive to the chosen data window.'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQFJiL8eklAkcUI5UUq_Mm8urLrO33hi-zMah6mOtuSmHAwsKgRdvQ86YU0XNEeGb6LdF28OoS6Z5ztcnfg2ih2-tWe1PaIIAOtq61j7S2iN1hPuzmLrhU3n09w-4RZAyvLRhe85Bh4TSiIej06wEKakQvBAgC4MTTqiZg=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Graph showing the peak effect on oil theft occurs four years post-election due to the required investment.', 'OIL THEFT IS AN INDUSTRIAL PIVOT REQUIRING TIME AND CAPITAL INVESTMENT\n\nFigure 7: Dynamic treatment effect of PAN\'s victory\n[Graph showing the "Effect on taps" from years -1 to 5 relative to the election. The effect remains near zero for years -1 to 1, then grows significantly, peaking at year 4.]\n\nThe effect is not immediate. It peaks four years after the election.\n\n\nFinal Policy Synthesis Box\nRepressing one criminal sector without dismantling the underlying organizational capital simply displaces the crime. Cartels used the intervening years to pay the fixed costs of heavy equipment and bribery, successfully \'leapfrogging\' into a highly organized, billion-dollar oil theft industry.']], 'https://contribution.usercontent.google.com/download?c=Cgpub3RlYm9va2xtEkYSD2FydGlmYWN0c19tZWRpYRozCiRiNzAxZWY2Yi0xMDhlLTQ2NDYtOTk2MS0xNjQ4NGEyMzYxYzASCxIHELeYmtjZERgB&filename=Drug_Wars_Fueling_Oil_Theft.pdf&opi=96797242', 'https://contribution.usercontent.google.com/download?c=Cgpub3RlYm9va2xtEkYSD2FydGlmYWN0c19tZWRpYRozCiRjMjliYmYzMi0zYWVlLTRhMzctOTVkMS01MTAzOTQ1ZDExMTISCxIHELeYmtjZERgB&filename=Drug_Wars_Fueling_Oil_Theft.pptx&opi=96797242'], None, None, 5, None, 'MTc3NDg2NzAxOS02MjYxNDAwMDA=']
DEBUG: Asset 1c41e288-db04-4612-97fb-1f4c2af2a1a0 type=8 status=3
DEBUG: Raw artifact: ['cf385f59-9e7a-4c24-b06d-e240e01f21fe', 'The Shadow Economy Blueprint', 8, [[['c2400f02-d8c4-40cc-8dea-ea871698e140']]], 3, None, None, None, None, None, [1774862450, 274028000], None, None, None, None, [1774861841, 370248000], [["Create a 15-slide presentation in English based on the paper 'Fueling Organized Crime: The Mexican War on Drugs and Oil Theft'. Use a professional academic tone.\n\nStructure:\n1. Title Slide: Title and authors (Battiston, Daniele, Le Moglie, Pinotti).\n2. Research Question & Motivation: Investigate if crackdowns on drugs unintentionally spur oil theft.\n3. Theoretical Framework: The 'Leapfrogging' model explaining why challenger cartels invest in new sectors.\n4. Institutional Context I: The Mexican War on Drugs started by Calderón in 2007.\n5. Institutional Context II: Large-scale oil theft via tapping Pemex pipelines.\n6. Empirical Strategy: Regression Discontinuity Design (RDD) focusing on local political alignment.\n7. Identification Strategy: Using PAN's margin of victory as the running variable to proxy crackdown intensity.\n8. RDD Validity I: Balancing tests on predetermined characteristics (geography, population, etc.) from Table A.9.\n9. RDD Validity II: McCrary density test to rule out manipulation of election results (Figure A.7).\n10. RDD Validity III: Placebo test for the year 2006 to show no pre-existing effect before the War on Drugs (Table A.10).\n11. RDD Main Results (Visual): Show the clear discontinuity in illegal taps at the cutoff (Figure 6).\n12. RDD Main Results (Estimates): Quantify the effect (+6.6 taps/year) and discuss specifications from Table 3.\n13. RDD Robustness I: Permutation tests with artificial cutoffs to confirm statistical significance (Figure A.10).\n14. RDD Robustness II: Sensitivity analysis showing stability across different bandwidths and polynomials (Figure A.8).\n15. Dynamic Effects & Policy Implications: Evolution of the effect over time (Figure 7) and the need for multi-sectoral enforcement.", 'en-US', 2, 3], 'The Shadow Economy Blueprint', [[['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQGS8lFZbUaMFWNdMvqNIAUStHqJ4tdYyv6c9KejmQFM2LTGegiJCAb_1XL6vvAMv-tyvcH4quITXHhUqrzYRev25oReCIKC1KKMdIw1RZDGWvenKD82YBj3n7L5DrvbLUAMHgv2Xzr4W_eFDUF6-ZbuKRBiuM4lLeJe_ME=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Title slide for "Fueling Organized Crime," an analysis of the Mexican war on drugs and oil theft by four authors.', 'FUELING ORGANIZED CRIME: THE MEXICAN WAR ON DRUGS AND OIL THEFT\n\nGiacomo Battiston, Gianmarco Daniele, Marco Le Moglie, Paolo Pinotti\n\nAn empirical analysis of policy-induced criminal displacement.\n\n[The background is split vertically. The left side features organic, red vein-like structures on a dark background. The right side shows a complex network of golden-orange industrial pipes with various valves.]'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQHznZOeABs4wsWNr3gMyQrAhSrN6di_n_J3ckwy9M5QUpsJo5MV1yT7FJWlOU3vkaUQCeeKo2AH6H3ShOZk3YAEXzmCW5YeczaWaGAITCo4G2BE3WNHBS7Xw4rXtE1kkncDJjF0lw0V5PxPMyBYKwVK13zVJ_CI2vJ8dQ=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Diagram showing how crackdowns on drug trafficking can redirect criminal activity into emerging sectors like oil theft.', 'THE SHADOW ECONOMY\n\nTHE UNINTENDED CONSEQUENCES OF SECTOR-SPECIFIC ENFORCEMENT\n\n[A cross-section diagram of a U-shaped pipe. On the left, a heavy weight labeled Targeted Government Crackdown is being pushed down into a red fluid labeled Traditional Sector (Drug Trafficking). Arrows indicate the fluid is being forced through the bottom of the U and up the right side.]\n\n[The right side of the pipe contains an orange fluid labeled Emerging Sector (Oil Theft), which is expanding and bulging the side of the pipe.]\n\nResearch Question: Do government crackdowns on one criminal sector unintentionally spur expansion into new, illicit markets?\n\nThe Paradox: Eradicating a primary illicit market does not necessarily destroy criminal organizations; it may forcibly redirect their capital and operations into untapped, parallel economies.'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQEcftxS3c_d86NMctepSPglXOYzaHVMyod1Ffk16byWPvqaF7JwhNrUwpo8SkA3usces1DGaZSZpFH3xKSSpO5OuJ7d8uYAZ6DRRt6rJnZHVP2doX_JabwcJrwnSvEDs6SnnI3REt6t3yTMWD-aUh-99KgXaGIXAOMqGl0=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'A matrix explaining how challenger cartels "leapfrog" incumbents by moving into new illicit sectors like oil theft.', 'THE \'LEAPFROGGING\' MODEL OF CRIMINAL INNOVATION\n\n[A 2x2 matrix with rows labeled Cartel Type: Incumbents and Challengers, and columns labeled Criminal Sector: Traditional (Drugs) and New (Oil).]\n\n- Incumbents / Traditional (Drugs): High comparative advantage. Retain dominance despite crackdowns.\n- Incumbents / New (Oil): Low incentive to pivot. Profit margins remain safer in established drug routes.\n- Challengers / Traditional (Drugs): Weak market share. Squeezed out by intense competition and state pressure.\n- Challengers / New (Oil): THE LEAPFROG ZONE. High incentive to pay the initial fixed investment cost to bypass incumbents and dominate a new monopoly. [This cell is highlighted with an orange border.]\n\nKey Insight: Crackdowns incentivize challenger cartels—who hold residual shares in traditional markets—to "leapfrog" dominant incumbents by investing in entirely new illicit sectors.'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQHppvf2VBJr0w_M9i8CS2OXIHud8l-20F_elEuZhBrZ2QUrGJejruGi8o4GyrjJfHQNo18QuZwDQgMnEme8UYNrvrhsh1Nv0wVXlWB9gBVDBM5J2ptxwaTCLslBtC-5E7BG4Lsac8YSxZrKXdlxU3z1AoKa1nhsIRgT23o=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Line graph showing the homicide rate in Mexico more than tripling after the 2007 launch of the war on drugs.', 'THE SHOCK TO THE TRADITIONAL MARKET: THE 2007 WAR ON DRUGS\n\n[A line graph plots Homicide rate per 100,000 inhabitants from the year 2000 to 2018. A vertical red line marks 2007 with the label: 2007: Calderón Launches War on Drugs.]\n\n[The graph shows the homicide rate hovering around 10-12 until 2007, then sharply rising to nearly 25 by 2010. It dips slightly to 17 by 2014, before surging again to nearly 30 by 2018.]\n\nContext: Newly-appointed President Felipe Calderón (PAN) launches a massive military campaign against existing drug cartels.\n\nThe Result: The breakdown of the existing criminal equilibrium. The homicide rate more than triples—from 8 to 29 per 100,000 inhabitants by 2018—driven by state conflict and the fragmentation of legacy cartels.'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQF0NjpNjZGdqAaYzKDWlR_gMwir-WN14Yq_tk2BxG_QwmSELA2xGnpaBCQhrqpXed8qpc8WZ14_sd2ti2QFZ77falP-fECVM3xVXGsJBQUr8TI9dB6bQbrgmBJJ6UkfIgKxXm70SdJLLWKmbBuc29fzwkf1FHc4-HJXTQ=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Map and graph showing a massive increase in illegal oil pipeline taps in Mexico from 2007 to 2018.', "THE EMERGENCE OF THE NEW MARKET: INDUSTRIAL-SCALE OIL THEFT\n\n[A map of Mexico shows a dense network of orange lines representing Pemex pipelines.]\n\n[A line graph plots Total Number of Illegal Taps from 2000 to 2018. A vertical dashed orange line marks 2007. The number of taps remains very low near zero until 2007, then grows exponentially, reaching over 15,000 taps by 2018.]\n\nContext: Mexico's state-owned Pemex pipelines present a vast, unguarded geographic vulnerability.\n\nThe Surge: Illegal taps transform from rudimentary local theft into a sophisticated, cartel-controlled industrial operation.\n\nScale: Taps escalate from a few hundred per year pre-2007 to over 15,000 by 2018, representing an illicit market value of $1-2 billion US annually."], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQEEHJe2pkub8HYN-bOWB3G9AtdSC8KoRdcHggeit_l-ILMN4_-9KvYeq9ET2AUX4tuVPEBC4t8jqk2Cmz6omb40owg6hUc41cX6zvzJKaDVA6TtUpid8XL8ms9jGN1YhIVjeANcGMh29qM88m3KiuFFzX5EZd9OZFGzzsY=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Flowchart describing the strategy of using PAN mayoral victories as a proxy to isolate drug crackdown intensity.', "EMPIRICAL STRATEGY: ISOLATING CRACKDOWN INTENSITY\n\n[A flowchart with four connected boxes:]\n- PAN Mayoral Victory (2007-2009 Elections)\n- [Arrow to] Federal-Local Alignment & Coordination\n- [Arrow to] Intense Local Drug Crackdown\n- [Arrow to] Cartel Displacement to Oil Theft\n\nThe Premise: Directly measuring 'crackdown intensity' is impossible without conflating it with crime reporting rates.\n\nThe Proxy: Based on Dell (2015), local political alignment with the ruling federal PAN party drove the deployment of troops and the severity of local anti-drug enforcement.\n\nThe Approach: Compare pipeline municipalities where the PAN narrowly won vs. narrowly lost to isolate the causal effect of state pressure."], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQH2O-a3fu8rJ1XAmQXkV501V7D1KT8GRLTYrnKf2w6Jr3kgY0FlOjTDIxQE1w9ujjtEyS51TmcWcGV5iS4JDqFoqb7hR1QDIV7H4sewVsmd68X88y2WywdX9xBRCF8RU45i8eyNLzNr-RhAy6fpzfFKNaxDjLi45H4NJjU=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Diagram showing the Regression Discontinuity Design comparing municipalities where the PAN narrowly won or lost.', "IDENTIFICATION STRATEGY: THE ELECTORAL MARGIN\n\n[A diagram of a horizontal line with 0 at the center.]\n- To the left of 0: Control Group: PAN Narrowly Loses\n- To the right of 0: Treatment Group: PAN Narrowly Wins\n\nRunning Variable: The PAN candidate's margin of victory in the 2007-2009 municipal elections.\n\nThe Logic: Elections won or lost by a fraction of a percent are as good as random. Municipalities just to the left and right of the zero-margin threshold are statistically identical in every way—except for the intensity of the federal drug crackdown they experienced."], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQFtMzOeWv9E6NXRE7TYmUJFCjWmM6iockxPIoCvCgcG3q2DKGjw3f_vJmCGK4utRY9_Dt0VA3576WSwqejpbUR6yZyVRzjEcHkcbs-ENewqXjP3MJHV_ybfFwo52FsVZuALyXZrrj10Bli_ps1H2QaSpyx6FaoSVX66ffs=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Dashboard showing that control and treatment groups are balanced across geography, demographics, violence, and output.', 'RDD VALIDITY I: PRE-TREATMENT BALANCE\n\nKey Finding: Municipalities on either side of the electoral cutoff are virtually identical before the intervention.\n\n[Icon of a balanced scale.]\n\nMethodological Dashboard\n- Geography: Surface area, altitude, slope, distance to US border [Checked]\n- Demographics: Population size [Checked]\n- Baseline Violence: 2006 Homicide rate [Checked]\n- Economic Output: 2005 Night-time light density [Checked]'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQEjYQaUbCHUMJWxY2R4QnChn8vZB2uH8St3fj_1sA-23qpDvf-yZXayL7sxVeZU9bUAnED_JJSEemEMFGRSlvzZIuQeA5t7KnEvZ0T4nCLMKq7zXlDqsGTHnqOSymwvBKj99P9JIfI13tSCrBYIZIhMQfLEPjHtnrLZMBY=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'McCrary Density Test graph showing no manipulation of election results around the PAN victory threshold.', "RDD VALIDITY II: RULING OUT ELECTORAL MANIPULATION\n\n[A scatter plot and fitted curve representing the McCrary Density Test. The x-axis is PAN's margin of victory/loss, with a vertical dashed red line at 0. The points and the curve are continuous and smooth across the 0 threshold, showing no abrupt jump or drop in density.]\n\nThe Test: McCrary Density Test for manipulation of the running variable.\n\nThe Concern: Did cartels or political machines systematically rig the closest elections to avoid or invite the PAN crackdown?\n\nThe Proof: The smooth density curve at the cutoff confirms no unnatural clustering. The narrow victories and losses occurred naturally, preserving the quasi-experimental design."], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQF9dS3zpJnLJ6PfZn5w5OmJoXxOnUOhKQQ41Klkgn2qq4WOqB3m64vnAaUChUolRwLk0oILv65RzCTkeV1kuf_8ll7vMKsBfBOtRI-JXEemYhmTI0cFerjV7fxigLlHn68L8KVJolx1JZAy7pruSMfQLYkpW48qCHaiNGA=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Placebo test graph showing no pre-existing difference in oil theft between PAN and non-PAN municipalities in 2006.', 'RDD VALIDITY III: THE 2006 PLACEBO TEST\n\n[A scatter plot showing Illegal Oil Taps on the y-axis and PAN Margin of Victory on the x-axis. A vertical black line marks the 0 electoral cutoff. A horizontal white line passes through the data points, which are scattered randomly with no discontinuity or trend change at the 0 threshold.]\n\nThe Test: Did PAN-aligned municipalities simply have a pre-existing affinity for oil theft?\n\nThe Proof: Analyzing the year before the War on Drugs (2006) reveals a perfectly continuous flatline.\n\nConclusion: There was absolutely zero difference in illegal oil tapping between these municipalities prior to the federal crackdown. The displacement effect was triggered entirely by the policy intervention.'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQEBLlA-_1AtntJR_PobViL51zjZuYKHyZqEDn9N1tSo00WOu8pNFGdwvAtn5vbgNHPuytPwaqHKAukI04qJ8-Ft2xfUeQppNkEw6fL26lgizYLNGJhehdEMqVXzND3y0Ys0JLlyyaUGLwoSNl82-5AyGi2MoPxe2Cr4mg=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'RDD graph showing a sharp increase in illegal oil taps in municipalities where the PAN narrowly won.', "THE DISPLACEMENT EFFECT: CRACKDOWNS FUEL OIL THEFT\n\nA distinct, unmistakable discontinuity in illegal oil pipeline taps exactly at the threshold of a PAN electoral victory.\n\n[A regression discontinuity plot with Illegal taps on the y-axis and PAN's margin of victory/loss on the x-axis. To the left of the 0 threshold, data points are low and follow a slightly downward-sloping linear fit. Exactly at 0, there is a large vertical jump. To the right of 0, the data points are significantly higher and follow a slightly upward-sloping linear fit.]"], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQHlkETHyulz-513cmH1XoxJedk3fDh7gO6cA2wPp1Bcsfhv8BNnsgCRfjaJ99taSTlY_z6u6ZC1HE9UiH5yPH0VcHDxwR3sLFexJauzcxPUkm4-pCViEq5FRH2ygljmhWysp2wHKSRd4sJhOYCEIGB87rZKkFWphCXOWTc=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Summary of the displacement effect, showing an average increase of 6.6 oil taps per year after a PAN victory.', 'QUANTIFYING THE DISPLACEMENT\n\n+ 6.6 Taps / Year\n\nA marginal PAN victory caused an immediate, massive increase in local oil taps. This represents more than double the baseline average (5.3 taps/year) for municipalities with pipelines.\n\nRobust Estimates\n- Specification: Linear Baseline; Estimate: +6.6**; Fixed Effects: None\n- Specification: Quadratic; Estimate: +9.1**; Fixed Effects: None\n- Specification: Linear (Strict); Estimate: +4.0*; Fixed Effects: State & Year\n\nRobustness Note: The effect remains large and highly statistically significant across linear and quadratic specifications, even when controlling for state and year fixed effects.'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQFCGPONZWVSUyGxpGkouejPqnOHi9jENYaQEP6Z2gfbQtDDhl0D7caBykpNthZFLVpzNShRTKL3GBIszLwr2zaYCnqBdger4nDg1IJQfmVQQQkTZcTQs4eQqQlmA5pKLlImbyX1JObaLB5RH78uPMDjXCsbHB7e2cevAJo=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Histogram showing that the actual estimate of oil theft displacement is an extreme anomaly compared to random tests.', 'ROBUSTNESS I: PERMUTATION TESTS\n\n10,000 Placebo Cutoffs\n\n[A histogram showing the distribution of estimates from 10,000 placebo tests centered around 0. A vertical orange line labeled Actual Estimate: 9.065 is positioned at the far right tail of the distribution.]\n\nThe Test: What if we randomly assigned the "victory" cutoff to fake, arbitrary vote margins? Would we still see a jump?\n\nThe Proof: Testing 10,000 artificial cutoffs proves our finding is an extreme anomaly. The estimated coefficient at the true electoral cutoff sits above the 95th percentile of the placebo distribution. The effect is undeniable and non-random.'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQE5c0gJVrWpMm8SXdpUjTfTqwBhSaYTe-m52CVLyi2bLXzHnBEl5DiAEsxYIWXij1dBR8tkZaPkodzdRiqBbv1CqF6NU4tQKbtBOkqHlsVWryK2vBtBXzUkgayTnD5JK6zc_vJfJDhPjcjwm-KoBtKvHpyslqLlvR-AdeE=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Small multiples of RDD graphs showing that the increase in oil theft is robust across different mathematical models.', 'ROBUSTNESS II: SENSITIVITY ANALYSIS\n\nSmall Multiples\n\n[Four RDD graphs showing Illegal Taps vs PAN Margin, each displaying a sharp jump at the 0 threshold:]\n- Linear Fit (Narrow Bandwidth)\n- Smoothed Fit (Narrow Bandwidth)\n- Linear Fit (Wide Bandwidth)\n- Smoothed Fit (Wide Bandwidth)\n\nThe Test: Ensuring the discontinuity survives different mathematical assumptions.\n\nThe Proof: The massive increase in oil theft remains stable and significant regardless of the bandwidth width, polynomial degree, or kernel choice. The displacement is structural, not statistical.'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQFehaGDRLPYWFM8TjcxM-F88lFgG9BCZxQhibXirf__ZK_DSU3buRq4WSqQnDqtJUhsORTyeYN0vdumUizks7ZqCqPZvHE5J9at_XvYiIFyDMrMt73zBfqNrMKzrcIGbXDWFhqh8p2BXL2JYwVdAVLrjtPn5mtxVRnmKA=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Graph and text explaining that criminal displacement peaks four years after a crackdown, requiring holistic policy.', "DYNAMIC EFFECTS & POLICY IMPLICATIONS\n\n[A line graph plots Effect on taps on the y-axis and Years to/from election on the x-axis, ranging from -1 to 5. The effect is 0 at year 0, then steadily rises, peaking at 20 in year 4, before dipping slightly in year 5.]\n\n- Evolution: The displacement into oil theft is not instantaneous; it peaks four years post-crackdown as challenger cartels fully operationalize their leapfrog investments.\n\nTHE POLICY TAKEAWAY:\nSingle-sector enforcement acts as a localized pressure valve, displacing crime rather than destroying it. Effective state crackdowns require holistic, multi-sectoral enforcement that targets the organization's total illicit capital and infrastructure, rather than playing whack-a-mole with individual markets."]], 'https://contribution.usercontent.google.com/download?c=Cgpub3RlYm9va2xtEkYSD2FydGlmYWN0c19tZWRpYRozCiQxNGY2YzMyNC1iMGE2LTRmOWMtYWQ4MC1mOTcxNmMxMDYxNzQSCxIHELeYmtjZERgB&filename=The_Shadow_Economy_Blueprint.pdf&opi=96797242', 'https://contribution.usercontent.google.com/download?c=Cgpub3RlYm9va2xtEkYSD2FydGlmYWN0c19tZWRpYRozCiQ0NmNkNDg1NC1mYzE1LTRmMTItOWM5MS0zNGRmY2M3MjgwMjgSCxIHELeYmtjZERgB&filename=The_Shadow_Economy_Blueprint.pptx&opi=96797242'], None, None, 5, None, 'MTc3NDg2MjQ1MC0yNzQwMjgwMDA=']
