DEBUG: Raw artifact: ['45a02a5d-293f-41ee-90d2-0ab3d390bbaf', 'Immigration Perceptions and Redistribution', 8, [[['24b1a81e-e526-4ae5-91bd-81283fe16f49']]], 3, None, None, None, None, None, [1771965196, 613585000], None, None, None, None, [1771964664, 262534000], [["Vorrei una presentazione del paper per degli studenti di un corso di policy evaluation di triennale, che si soffermi soprattutto sull'analisi sperimentale, descrivendola nei dettagli. E'importante anche che la presentazione riporti le principali figure e tabelle con i risultati del paper sia descrittivi che causali. La presentazione non deve essere lunga piu di 20 slides. Questa è una presentazione inserita nel contesto di fare degli esempi di randomized control trials facendo vedere come questi possono essere impleentati anche attraverso delle survey. ", 'en', 1, 3], 'Immigration Perceptions and Redistribution', [[['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQFtXcNxwIR3O_E0BsdTZ2pSRfL4ji6RBHnUXObYAI50Q-CBcoD8sxCFetgcslrGAS5ZYs-1U8lv4Mre62dqVocS1Am_ai_2CnO4WgS3Ytx4oAJHVZ0QiNXWbaOWNx5j9t6vyED2ZWidfyeI2dDWjBUX_aL_cmNDr9YOuA=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Title slide for a survey-based experimental analysis on immigration and redistribution across the US and Europe.', 'IMMIGRATION AND REDISTRIBUTION: A SURVEY-BASED EXPERIMENTAL ANALYSIS\n\nA methodological case study based on Alesina, Miano, & Stantcheva (2022)\n\n[A map graphic titled Fig 1. Geographic Scope of the Study highlights the United States, United Kingdom, France, Italy, Germany, and Sweden in blue.]\n\nCourse: Policy Evaluation | Topic: Experimental Analysis in Surveys'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQHwwNC5NL2gtxQNl032T47tHX_1GFKtKzs36umMMen9m7BjamoGS1Xobqwj7A5pz598K36xo8SCbGU56NDezmN-hD12AHEZIcI3CbJTNgte8IG9OU7IM0fMlqQx9RDSsDJNiJwXHo-sSNrCBErx0dUcEvaWCLNDNbx05io=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], "Introduction to the Anti-Solidarity and Compensation hypotheses regarding immigration's impact on welfare support.", 'DOES IMMIGRATION ERODE SUPPORT FOR THE WELFARE STATE?\n\n- The Anti-Solidarity Hypothesis: Voters dislike redistributing towards out-groups. Voters may perceive immigrants as distinct out-groups, leading to a reduced willingness to support social welfare programs that might benefit them, potentially eroding overall public solidarity and support for redistribution mechanisms.\n\n- The Compensation Hypothesis: Voters want more social insurance to protect against labor market competition. Voters may feel increased economic insecurity due to potential labor market competition from immigrants, leading them to demand stronger social insurance and welfare policies as a form of compensation and protection against risks.\n\n[A diagram titled Perception of Immigrants shows a fraction with Immigrant/Misperception over Native/Reality. An arrow labeled Impact on... points down to a box labeled Support for Redistribution.]\n\nPolicy Briefing: Global Migration & Social Policy | Fall 2024 | Page 1'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQGsOBs0mZ-MjOYzXBnSq4z1F4wYp-Wm5PNg5_nadTR6hM996h3Z3eIPOFEX6j2rNLY4pM05B8lb6wt2KlcVwCbxSZm_7PA3JAksmnmyBUlHYcF_sq8b3yZrjlxC3kA_vCcRCgQ01Vpv8NQhLwZO-zthXgdaMm9Mf0auwg=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Bar chart displaying survey sample sizes for six countries, totaling 22,506 respondents.', 'THE INSTRUMENT: LARGE-SCALE CROSS-COUNTRY SURVEY.\n\nSample Sizes Per Country\n- US: 4,500\n- UK: 4,001\n- France: 4,000\n- Italy: 4,000\n- Germany: 4,001\n- Sweden: 2,004\n\nTotal N = 22,506\n\nTarget Population: Documented Immigrants.\nDefinition: People legally living in the country but born abroad.\nNote: Excludes illegal entry to isolate economic/social cohesion factors.\n\nPolicy Briefing: Global Migration & Social Policy | Fall 2024 | Page 2'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQFARt2dkfpl2QAdEKUnXHX8NTqjj1CY78LB_oOR6JP-6iiPc9uK5NmbzD9b8GxSqvyGc6f4jXIQmuz5z5GuM12gTSuBDsxe7rcJqjTAawK7o3uuDFuXpZX0TuPQVYOqzrsbecUhEkvrzkWvAEuvVU4MMgMMWfoIJ2xHx_M=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Explanation of visual design innovations used to elicit participant beliefs about immigrant population shares.', 'ELICITING BELIEFS: VISUAL DESIGN INNOVATIONS\n\n[A pie chart titled U.S. population by country of birth shows 14% Foreign born in orange and 86% U.S. born in blue. Below it is an interactive slider scale from 0 to 100 with a handle set at 14.]\n\n- 1 Benchmarking: Forces user to see the zero-sum trade-off (High Immigrant Share = Low Native Share). [Arrow points to the pie chart]\n\n- 2 Interaction: Requires cognitive effort, reducing careless answers. [Arrow points to the slider handle]\n\n- 3 Precision: Prevents "round number bias" (e.g., guessing 10% or 20%). [Arrow points to the slider axis]\n\nPolicy Briefing: Global Migration & Social Policy | Fall 2024 | Page 3'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQE_k6l0ymatskzzlY5zT-mHKA0Vk9ll1moSg4ZwOVTnEOSHSBzi_FtNorCIDunZan3k_SOcQ1W_7ku_EzPpVHrXy2WEAeOd7ObG3eQavKTbLAc2yR5QwmA7Tu3AA40VYrILpeD7WnTCfMjilBzVj1BPm2sKr6PTtEbZSp0=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Comparison chart showing that respondents in all six countries massively overestimate the actual share of immigrants.', 'THE REALITY GAP: PERCEPTION VS. FACT\n\n[A chart compares Actual Share (blue circles) to Perceived Share (orange circles) connected by a horizontal line across six countries:]\n- US: ~10% actual vs ~36% perceived\n- Italy: ~10% actual vs ~26% perceived\n- France: ~12% actual vs ~28% perceived\n- UK: ~13% actual vs ~30% perceived\n- Germany: ~15% actual vs ~37% perceived\n- Sweden: ~18% actual vs ~27% perceived\n\nRespondents in all six countries massively overestimate the number of immigrants.\n\nPolicy Briefing: Global Migration & Social Policy | Fall 2024 | Page 4'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQGVt2F5oFdx-JqcKYT6Doffq1b9zv8u-SZAOtRTL3WYuoFswRc5PGe1_L2eNiBKiHFouZGpj9xOQdbo73Wh03Cqr26K8d0ZXet9pk_jfAtig4dliTJpEO4kSOI267hjWECQ2COl1JASB3_KsLXDZ6xOL69GrLp7qIvfcw=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Summary of qualitative misperceptions that drive the "free-rider" stereotype of immigrants.', 'QUALITATIVE MISPERCEPTIONS: THE ‘FREE-RIDER’ STEREOTYPE\n\n- Underestimate Education Levels [Down arrow icon next to a graduation cap]\n- Overestimate Share of Muslims [Up arrow icon next to a crescent and star]\n- Overestimate Poverty & Unemployment [Up arrow icon next to a hand holding coins]\n\nThe prevailing belief is that immigrants are culturally distant, economically weak, and reliant on government transfers.\n\nPolicy Briefing: Global Migration & Social Policy | Fall 2024 | Page 5'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQHCJE-G8w650BVBI7I77tSR1jk1hHNUT2o8oZ84LLV-dSqufmmnzhSZzA5KIuKvne02sKH4Gk86NW9ABW_fNj6Trl2N2_t6Ve-j7EmhWXnImmog2hRA8C6QETCvCtCMwdisIsZ83Z2tIpDGaPo6l3NkcxCYsgKptoo6Mkw=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'The "John vs. Mohammad" test demonstrates identity-based bias despite identical economic profiles.', 'MEASURING BIAS: THE ‘JOHN VS. MOHAMMAD’ TEST\n\n[Two ID cards show identical data except for the name. Card 1: John, Age 30, Income $35,000, Family Married, 2 kids. Card 2: Mohammad, Age 30, Income $35,000, Family Married, 2 kids.]\n\nQuestion: Who pays more taxes? Who receives more transfers?\n\nResult: Despite identical economic profiles, ‘Mohammad’ is perceived as paying fewer taxes and taking more handouts. This isolates identity-based bias.\n\nPolicy Briefing: Global Migration & Social Policy | Fall 2024 | Page 6'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQEWXNugHwvAsUYq912eIWOhegXjIpYDIHNDPDrxSc9uYoy3hBD9NQk3yAWEmgXDlCky-_6PBeWVQINmM_K9akJy96yMB99FxirGHA8O4KZjfT_2LFpC8l66rWM0U1SXqWUfObmaneKPxdOrhoKFo3BnB95657WRlqi3Ru0=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Flowchart showing the Randomized Controlled Trial design, from background questions to outcome measurement.', 'EXPERIMENTAL DESIGN: THE RCT FLOWCHART\n\n[A flowchart moves from left to right through four stages:]\n\n1. Background Questions: Demographics, Sector.\n\n2. Randomization 1: Information Treatment. [Sub-options: Control, Share Video, Origins Video, Hard Work Video]\n\n3. Randomization 2: Order/Priming. [Sub-options: Immigration First, Redistribution First]\n\n4. Outcomes: Tax Views, Spending, Donation.\n\nPolicy Briefing: Global Migration & Social Policy | Fall 2024 | Page 7'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQHWDZYIPk2r11YaeJBGvdEVbdmH2DcY0YT4wgrgV83M56SYS7T4luLVtfBpnTfIOCOZSy0LdmVjdVBNL7J69GG_O4NzkNQ8iQ1jiSvFfdZfm7_iAJuRnHTW0Xl3pCMnA-U5SsA5pzXUUxgP33rG-5ZGtWIIk43waHZ5pUg=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Explanation of the priming treatment arm used to test the effect of thinking about immigration on welfare support.', 'TREATMENT ARM 1: PRIMING (SALIENCE)\n\nSalience Condition\n[Arrow points from Immigration Questions to Tax/Redistribution Questions]\n\nControl Condition\n[Arrow points from Tax/Redistribution Questions to Immigration Questions]\n\nMechanism: Does the mere act of thinking about immigration first make people less supportive of redistribution?\n\nThis mimics political campaigns that keep immigration ‘top of mind’.\n\nPolicy Briefing: Global Migration & Social Policy | Fall 2024 | Page 8'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQFW6pgTdVmNNl80MbpSLjfuAHn9BlMl0iuxYeEKF6jmx7sLY48xpvSCMeR1pcISdBCgXxcVThGnnU8YF-S4c7rfvlBL4QWSFruCeTP8R62xFqBCNW5Ovy4pVQhQHj_B-NqYIdXGVWcERW6EUpmfBOfmevoaOyybE5hTBg=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Comparison of treatment types providing statistical facts versus a narrative story about hard-working immigrants.', 'TREATMENT ARM 2: INFORMATION VS. NARRATIVE\n\n- The Share: [Pie chart showing 10%] Today, legal immigrants make up 10% of the United States population.\n\n- The Origins: [World map with arrows pointing to the US] Looking at the U.S. today, where do they come from?\n\n- The Narrative: [Silhouette of a construction worker] Hard Work Anecdote.\n\nTreatments 1 & 2 provide statistical facts. Treatment 3 provides a story to counter the “Free Rider” stereotype.\n\nPolicy Briefing: Global Migration & Social Policy | Fall 2024 | Page 9'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQFCiwRqizDCdzdH88unLjXCQXoZTeJqO5Up8OYFojAhqsOF8JKFyPym9hgJWnk9LfUloTurqVFaF08f1PA6GOcCQGuejS717a-jM5jfO25_hDlsvrTt24ohwFejs0fCASi8H3-MVYc-hEWE_5_pGA3Dnlh1-NXVp4pzHCo=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Distinction between stated preferences and revealed preferences in measuring altruistic outcomes.', 'MEASURING OUTCOMES: STATED VS. REVEALED PREFERENCES\n\n- Stated Preference: [Clipboard icon] Tax rates, Budget allocation.\n\n- Revealed Preference: [Icons of a dollar bill and a donation box] Respondents commit real money to charity pouner befents to before knowing if they won on the lottery. This measures true altruism.\n\nPolicy Briefing: Global Migration & Social Policy | Fall 2024 | Page 10'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQH74iBIkiFdIM_jIFeiSPAi6nghn9c-JfYCa3EcTiL-G5J7K-86UWolBevagy9WzDMiHWiSMArCrupV-xA5kqmSg1S6-gBA2WfSm5qZGXCPytcwvCfnwMXWzfQgX8HMZaw3VEWVunbsUw5n09ZJMn9YxqxRKLpubJzyMww=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Results showing that priming respondents with immigration first reduces support for redistribution and charity.', 'RESULT 1: THE PRIMING EFFECT\n\nEffect of “Immigration First” Order on Redistribution Support\n\n[A bar chart shows negative effects on a scale from 0 to -4:]\n- Support for Progressive Tax: ~ -3.5\n- Support for Safety Net: ~ -2.6\n- Donation to Charity: ~ -1.7\n\nSimply thinking about immigration significantly reduces generosity towards the poor, even when no negative information is provided.\n\nPolicy Briefing: Global Migration & Social Policy | Fall 2024 | Page 11'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQH5HNSJosUBbJw_9QZyKj_PA5_e4yzS0s1x5or2az-vJGBSKj4oOflRtb-CGYY567CUdbP3iOHEWxziLv_4tgGR7GO1O_EG6RQqPH8fKREVnGPmwF5KdIiSpzyXnoeUny1f5ZOwBijwi6V_sG4I1QnAScqIQ5gvb03liFs=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Graph showing that a "hard work" narrative has a positive effect on support, while facts have zero effect.', 'RESULT 2: FACTS VS. NARRATIVES\n\nTreatment Effects on “Support for Redistribution”\n\n[A bar chart compares three treatments:]\n- Share of Immigrants Info: [Large gray bar reaching -4]\n- Origins Info: [Bar at 0]\n- Hard Work Narrative: [Small positive bar ~ +0.5]\n\nFacts (Share/Origins) have zero effect. The ‘Hard Work’ story has a positive effect but cannot fully overturn the negative priming.\n\nPolicy Briefing: Global Migration & Social Policy | Fall 2024 | Page 12'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQHDUj51h7VDvIfCrvmJk9OYsScapSlV3LX4E5Z-QiWi28NjUgLTTBpgEkivIzzFCx65siPHZStoOXpbb3TJ666HODRidFfRKcWYZdx_5LH678mT3R251KDHzF2-p2BdaAtCG3vA2mnFLXur8aKazr5sb15zSrs1cL8TIf0=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Chart identifying the "free-rider" belief as the strongest predictor of anti-redistribution sentiment.', 'MECHANISM: WHAT DRIVES ANTI-REDISTRIBUTION?\n\nPredictors of Anti-Redistribution Sentiment\n\n[A horizontal bar chart shows relative predictive strength:]\n- Belief that immigrants Free-Ride: (Highest strength)\n- Belief that immigrants are Poor/Uneducated: (Moderate strength)\n- Cultural Distance: (Low strength)\n- Total Number of Immigrants: (Lowest strength)\n\nThe strongest predictor is the belief that immigrants take welfare without working (‘Free-Riders’), not their race or religion.\n\nPolicy Briefing: Global Migration & Social Policy | Fall 2024 | Page 13'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQGrmsRyaFUXaEXr9vKrGN_su66nfxG1kAiKV09Dp4myYweiBTin4PFUmIN81yPKKCYagR3kRtFurjgD1FmYVEYe_O7edwCDtwdfVxqOlWgNX66EJ1lfO3kIOqrq37Y7Tb8dfcd0mSt-MHQ93dJ4gcG-VTHPwO4CG1y9Uik=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Overview of methodological quality controls, including attention trap questions and time tracking.', 'METHODOLOGICAL QUALITY CONTROL\n\n- Attention: [Eye icon] Trap questions (e.g., “Select strongly agree”) had a 99.5% pass rate.\n\n- Time Tracking: [Stopwatch icon] Respondents rushing (bottom 2%) or distracted (top 2%) were dropped.\n\n- Incentives: [Dollar symbol icon] Paying for accuracy did not reduce misperceptions. Conclusion: Misperceptions are sincere, not lazy.\n\nPolicy Briefing: Global Migration & Social Policy | Fall 2024 | Page 14'], [['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQFA1l0TYurSqtVvRJKAMBpEDrhq-gJ5NpLB1EqaWSTCeZFf2pMDVMgIDsyJpK33RA_Xs1BrVbTl4JaYpYGQOXQXUGBj5nV6lf2BwZa2xwzIBB-8XeubxuGNpkAY66utBspwZmN-oY9RQGhoTcawWFoA95RWm3jJoFOpeyc=w1376-h768', 1376, 768], 'Conclusions highlighting the stickiness of beliefs and the value of narrative over statistical correction.', 'CONCLUSIONS & LESSONS FOR POLICY EVALUATION.\n\n1. Stickiness of Beliefs: Misperceptions are widespread and resistant to factual correction.\n\n2. The Power of Narrative: Addressing the ‘Free Rider’ stereotype is more effective than correcting statistics.\n\n3. Experimental Value: Only an RCT embedded in a survey could isolate ‘Salience’ from ‘Information’ to prove that merely thinking about immigration lowers support for the welfare state.\n\nPolicy Briefing: Global Migration & Social Policy | Fall 2024 | Page 15']], 'https://contribution.usercontent.google.com/download?c=Cgpub3RlYm9va2xtEkYSD2FydGlmYWN0c19tZWRpYRozCiQwMWM3ZTBjOC00ZWNmLTRiMjMtOGY0OS0xM2Q5MzRlNTNjNjASCxIHELeYmtjZERgB&filename=Immigration_Perceptions_and_Redistribution.pdf&opi=96797242', 'https://contribution.usercontent.google.com/download?c=Cgpub3RlYm9va2xtEkYSD2FydGlmYWN0c19tZWRpYRozCiQ3Y2NhNTEzZS0zMDNkLTRkOTktYjU0My1hZDk1NDI4Zjc0MGYSCxIHELeYmtjZERgB&filename=Immigration_Perceptions_and_Redistribution.pptx&opi=96797242'], None, None, 1, None, 'MTc3MTk2NTE5Ni02MTM1ODUwMDA=']
