DEBUG: Raw artifact: ['1599cd04-58c4-4972-98fd-2228c348e34b', 'Racial Bias in Hiring Study', 7, [[['26ae1666-801d-4d06-a1f7-862e2abb31d7']]], 3, None, None, None, None, None, [1771681651, 490996000], None, None, None, [[None, 'en', None, 1, 2], 'Racial Bias in Hiring Study', [['Racial Bias in Hiring Study', ['https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/notebooklm/AKXwDQHAbVMzkGC7zsKNPn0oL2DMpMiH5Qg1oDI8HFPPYhcaRRsoA76XixeRsx5mmt9QlrYeGpDFe_GYOI5aCErt_nAs6ffweF24S3olxfsoQ7dAXo1IYnVIqNHqmCj-VTDWm6lpyZWJq-a6XFacq7ZO0PRz_LVd9-M=w2752-d-h1536-mp2', 2752, 1536], 'Infographic showing that White-sounding names receive significantly more job callbacks than African-American names.', 'MAIN TITLE AND OVERVIEW\n\nAre Emily and Greg More Employable Than Lakisha and Jamal?\nA field experiment in Boston and Chicago with nearly 5,000 fictitious resumes featuring identical qualifications tested the impact of perceived race on hiring through name associations.\n\n\nTHE CALLBACK GAP\n\n[A balance scale weighs two groups of resumes. The left side, containing a taller stack of blue and yellow resumes, is weighted lower than the right side.]\n\nWhite-Sounding Names (e.g., Emily, Greg):\n- 9.65% Mean Callback Rate.\n- 2,435 Resumes Sent.\n- 50% Higher Callback Rate: Resumes received one callback for every 10 sent.\n\nAfrican-American Names (e.g., Lakisha, Jamal):\n- 6.45% Mean Callback Rate.\n- African-American names required 15 resumes sent for one callback.\n\nA Name is Worth 8 Years:\n- [Icon of a clock face labeled 8 Years of Experience.]\n- The benefit of a White-sounding name is equivalent to adding eight years of work experience.\n\n\nDISCRIMINATION BY SECTOR\n\nDiscrimination is Universal Across Sectors:\n- The racial gap remained consistent across all occupations, industries, and employer sizes studied.\n- [Icons depict a corporate office, an industrial factory, and a retail storefront.]\n\n\nTHE SKILL PARADOX\n\nHigh-Quality White Applicants:\n- 30% Boost: White applicants saw a significant increase in callbacks when their resume quality and credentials improved.\n- [Visual shows a very tall stack of blue and yellow resumes.]\n\nHigh-Quality Black Applicants:\n- Negligible Effect.\n- No Reward: Improving credentials had a negligible effect on the callback rate for resumes with African-American names.\n- [Visual shows a much shorter stack of red and blue resumes.]\n\nThe Gap Widens with Qualifications:\n- As resume quality increases, the callback gap between White and African-American applicants actually expands.\n- [Visual features a rotary telephone and a secondary balance scale.]']]], [1771681489, 180247000], None, None, None, 1, None, 'MTc3MTY4MTY1MS00OTA5OTYwMDA=']
